<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Air Force Helicopters Crash in Nevada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Air Force
helicopters with 12 people on board crashed early Friday during a
training mission over Nevada.
</P>
<P>
The HH60G Pave Hawk helicopters from the Nellis Air Force Base
were on a night training missing when they crashed at about 4 a.m.
EDT, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the helicopters was found about an hour later,
but the fate of the people on board was unknown.
</P>
<P>
Major Byron James, an Air Force spokesman at the Pentagon, said
the two helicopters apparently collided.
</P>
<P>
A team of search and rescue and emergency forces from the Air
Force, Bureau of Land Management and Department of Energy were
working with local authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force owns only 10 of the Pave Hawk helicopters of the
type that crashed Friday. They normally carry a crew of four
people -- two pilots, a flight engineer and a gunner.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters, built by Sikorsky Aircraft Corp, are part of
the 66th Rescue Squadron, the largest rescue squadron in the Air
Force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
