<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Ahern for Pivotal Peace Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) - U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday lauded Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern for his important
role in bringing peace and prosperity to the island.
</P>
<P>
"The world owes you a debt of gratitude," Clinton said at a
reception of government, union, business and farming
representatives at the Royal College of Surgeons in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
"I just want to say to all of you, you can be very proud of his
leadership -- as well as your own overwhelming vote for peace a
few months ago," said the American president who is in Dublin for
a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
In a referendum in May, 95 percent of the Irish voters endorsed
the Northern Ireland peace agreement thrashed out a month ago,
which agrees to relinquish Dublin's constitutionally enshrined
claim on the six counties of Northern Ireland in return for more
involvement in their administration.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the peace deal would not have been signed in April
without Ahern, who had to take time out of the final week of the
talks to bury his mother.
</P>
<P>
"He led a campaign sometimes under great personal duress. His
pleas for peace began early in his service.... He has been
terrifically effective in working with Prime Minister Blair and
all the parties in both communities," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing I can say to you today is I hope you
will continue to be a model for the world in responsible
citizenship," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Dublin, Clinton held talks with the Irish
prime minister. He will visit the European center of U.S. computer
company Gateway 2000 on the outskirts of Dublin later in the day.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday Clinton will visit the western city of Limerick and
then head back to Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
