<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian President: Solve Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President
Nachagyn Bagabandy on Friday urged leaders of major parties to
find a way out of the current political crisis through
consultation.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to them, Bagabandy said that the Great Hural (the
Mongolian parliament) has sacked the government for 42 days, and a
new prime minister is yet to be found, an embarrassing situation
that should not go on.
</P>
<P>
The leaders include President of the Mongolian National
Democratic Party Tsakhiya Elbegdorj, Chairman of the Mongolian
Social Democratic Party Radnaasumberel Gonchigdorj and President
of the Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party N. Enhbayar.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy said the crisis looms large over Mongolia's political
and economic life.
</P>
<P>
Politically, the interim government has almost stopped
functioning since nobody listens to it.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the president said, voters have lost
confidence in the Great Hural and the government.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, economic hardships are deepening with social
unrest on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural on Wednesday rejected the nomination of
R. Amarjargal, acting minister of external affairs, as prime
minister, saying that no minister of the former government should
become new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Under fire for a bank merger, Mongolia's three-month old
coalition government led by Elbegdorj was dismissed on July 24
after losing a vote of confidence in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Afterward, the coalition repeatedly nominated Davaadorj
Ganbold, chairman of the Standing Committee of Economic Policy of
the Great Hural, who was turned down by the president five times.
</P>
<P>
In response to the situation, the minority Mongolian People's
Revolutionary Party made a statement recently, saying that the
unicameral Great Hural should be dissolved if it fails to appoint
a prime minister in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
