<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Organization Denies Involvement in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A body calling itself
the Unemployed Masses of South Africa (UMSA) Friday denied
responsibility for the deaths of three foreigners on a train near
Pretoria Thursday,
</P>
<P>
UMSA Vice-President Daniel Mohlatlole said he did not see any
of the organization's members beating anybody, as witnesses
claimed, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The three, two from Senegal and one from Mozambique, were
killed trying to flee from an angry mob accusing them of stealing
jobs from South Africans.
</P>
<P>
One man was apparently thrown from the train and was run over
by an oncoming train. The other two were electrocuted by overhead
wires when they climbed on the roof, trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
Police said UMSA members, who earlier in the day took part in
a protest march in Pretoria, were on the train.
</P>
<P>
Mohlatlole said two UMSA members tried to sjambok a foreigner
before getting on the train, but were ordered to stop by the
body's president, Godfrey Debeila.
</P>
<P>
"Godfrey told the two members they would be arrested if they
hit the man, and they then left it," Mohlatlole said.
</P>
<P>
He said UMSA members sat in about four carriages on the train.
"After a while we all joined our singing comrades in one
carriage, and this must be when the foreigners got scared and
tried to escape."
</P>
<P>
He said the chanting scared the foreigners away, and they were
responsible for their own deaths.
</P>
<P>
UMSA members were returning home from a march in Pretoria to
the Labor and Home Affairs Departments, where they demanded
illegal aliens be banned from the country because they were to
blame for the high unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
Police said no witnesses to the three deaths had come forward,
and no arrests were made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
