<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Reiterates Not to Devalue RMB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China is committed to not
devaluing its currency Renminbi in a hope to stablize the Asian
economy, Deng Nan, Chinese vice minister of science and
technology, said at a seminar here Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar focused on 21st century-oriented international
cooperation strategies, Deng said China's insisting on not
devaluing its currency is to lessen Asia's financial crisis and
stabilize the economy, thus contribute directly to the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the Asian financial crisis, what is the most
important is to unite all countries in efforts to help crisis-hit
countries and prevent the crisis from spreading, she said.
</P>
<P>
Every nation, while benefiting from the positive effect of the
economic globalization, should also made substantial contribution
to the elimination of its negative effect, Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Calling China the last front line to fend off the crisis, Deng
said China will take a series of more active measures to lessen
the impact of possible currency devaluation by its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Deng also introduced the economic progress made by China in the
past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Saying China has been active in international cooperation, she
called for more economic and scientific cooperation between China
and its foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
The "Today and Tomorrow Outlook for Cooperate Strategies"
seminar, held in the northern city Como, is scheduled to end
September 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
