<HEADLINE> BP to Transfer Retail Business in Belgium to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 4 (Xinhua) -- British Petroleum (BP)
has agreed to transfer its retail business in Belgium to Kuwait
Petroleum Corporation (KPC), the official Kuwait news agency Kuna
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The transfer, which involves 157 BP service stations and
relevant staff, will take effect on October 1, 1998, Kuna cited a
KPC statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
As of October 1, the newly acquired service stations will be
gradually rebranded in colors of Q8, brand name of KPC's global
service stations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
All staff who have their main activities related to the BP
retail service in Belgium will transfer to KPC and continue their
activities for Q8.
</P>
<P>
After the transfer, the KPC will have 320 Q8 service stations
and 20 international diesel service truck stations in Belgium,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
While not giving the reason of the BP transfer, the statement
said other BP businesses in Belgium will largely be unaffected.
</P>
<P>
The KPC statement said the acquisition represents an excellent
complement to KPC's activities and will strengthen and enhance the
competitive position of the state-owned conglomerate, adding the
transfer represents one more step in the development of KPC's
activities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The KPC bought a number of companies in the 1980s to build a
marketing outlet for Kuwaiti hydrocarbons in key European
countries. It also formed joint ventures in a number of European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Petroleum International (KPI), a subsidiary of KPC,
operates over 5,000 service stations in ten countries in Western
Europe, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
