<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xenophobia Growing Among S. Africans: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Resentment toward
foreigners among South Africans could spark a violent attacks
against illegal aliens, experts warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
Three foreigners, two from Senegal and one from Mozambique,
were killed on a train near Pretoria Thursday afternoon after a
mob accused them of stealing jobs from South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Two of the victims were electrocuted by overhead wires when
they tried to escape by climbing on the roof of the train. The
third was thrown out of a window and was run over by an oncoming
train.
</P>
<P>
Wrath toward illegal aliens was growing, and was especially
strong among black South Africans, South African Press
Association quoted a political scientist, Theo Bekker, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This is going to develop into a bloody battle if something is
not done," said Bekker of Pretoria University.
</P>
<P>
Steven Friedman, director of Center for Policy Studies, said:
"The scary part is the danger that a pattern will start
developing."
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that Thursday's incident was not the first of
its kind. More such assaults could be expected if intolerance
toward foreigners was not addressed.
</P>
<P>
Friedman said recent studies revealed a strong resentment
toward aliens, especially in Gauteng and Western Cape provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1994, there has been a heavy groundswell of
anti-foreigner sentiment among whites as well as blacks."
</P>
<P>
This claimed the lives of at least 20 foreigners in Cape Town
last year, some of them dying in incidents on passenger trains,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing that it was impossible to stop the flow of illegal
aliens, Friedman and Bekker said the government and politicians
should try to instill greater tolerance toward foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Friedman said there was nothing rational about hating all
illegal immigrants. The perception that they robbed South
Africans of jobs was not necessarily true. Many foreigners were
self-employed, and others were prepared to work for wages
unacceptable to South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Politicians had a duty to point out these realities, Friedman
said.
</P>
<P>
Bekker said South Africa simply did not have the resources to
stop all unwelcome immigrants entering the country.
</P>
<P>
The solution was economic development in neighboring countries
to produce job opportunities for those seeking a haven in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Until such time, the message from the government should be
that foreigners should be treated with leniency. If that doesn't
happen I see serious trouble coming," Bekker said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
