<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Rwandan PM Sentenced to Life Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) Friday sentenced Rwandan
former Prime Minister Jean Kambanda life imprisonment for
genocide and crimes against humanity despite his co-operation
given to the United Nations court.
</P>
<P>
This is the first sentence delivered by the court, and the
first ever sentence for genocide by an international court.
</P>
<P>
The maximum sentence the ICTR can impose is life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the defense counsel, Michael Ingliss from St.
Lucia, prayed for leniency, suggesting a two-year jail term would
be enough in the light of Kambanda's voluntary confession and
assistance he had given to prosecution and the court.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda, 43, admitted his command responsibility as Head of
Government, his participation in decisions to commit massacres of
Tutsis, and his active participation in the use of the media to
mobilize and incite massacre of civilian Tutsis, including using
the incendiary phrases which was subsequently repeatedly
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The court accepted his plea and found him guilty on all the
counts of his indictment.
</P>
<P>
The chamber said that "the aggravating circumstances
surrounding the crimes committed by Jean Kambanda negate the
mitigating circumstances, especially since Jean Kambanda occupied
a high ministerial post at the time he committed the said
crimes."
</P>
<P>
Kambanda, married with two children, holds a diploma of
engineer. During May of 1989 and April of 1994, he worked in the
Union des Banques Populaires du Rwanda and rose to the director.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda was Vice President of the Mouvement Democratique
Republicain (MDR) and member of its political bureau. On April 9,
1994, he became Prime Minister of the Interim Government in
Rwanda, following the plane crash that killed President Juvenal
Habyarimana on April 6.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus,
were brutally massacred in just three months in the middle of
that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernobyl Children Face Thyroid Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Young people exposed to
radioactive iodine released during the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear
disaster may be much more susceptible to have thyroid diseases,
scientists said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Writing in The Lancet medical journal, Dr Furio Pacini from the
University of Pisa, Italy, said that young people exposed to the
disaster 12 years ago were found to have developed antibodies
against the thyroid gland.
</P>
<P>
Antibodies fight infection, but sometimes they can attack the
body when the immune system is fooled into thinking that infection
has set in.
</P>
<P>
Although the new study found no evidence of thyroid dysfunction
in the young men and women, whose blood was tested six-eight years
after the disaster, researchers suggested that they may later
develop autoimmune thyroid diseases.
</P>
<P>
The antibodies may attack the thyroid gland controlling the
body's metabolism, and this may lead to a condition known as
hypothyroidism, which causes low metabolic rate, weight gain and
drowsiness in sufferers.
</P>
<P>
In their study, Dr Furio Pacini and colleagues from Italy and
Belarus carried out tests on the thyroids of young people from the
village heavily contaminated with radioactive fallout, and from a
second village which received negligible contamination.
</P>
<P>
The investigation showed no significant differences in thyroid
function between the two groups, but found that youngsters from
the contaminated village were five times more likely to have
developed anti-thyroid gland antibodies.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of future development of hypothyroidism in the
people of Belarus exposed to fallout should be considered," the
researchers concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
