<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile Fever Has Spread to Europe, Doctors Warn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- West Nile fever, an infection
which is carried by mosquitoes and is common in Africa, Asia and
the Middle East, has entered Europe, doctors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
An epidemic of the disease, which can cause meningitis and
inflammation of the brain known as encephalitis, has been
identified in Romania, Dr Ted Tsai and colleagues from the United
States and Romania reported in The Lancet medical journal.
</P>
<P>
In August 1996, doctors in two infectious disease hospitals in
the Romanian capital Bucharest noticed a rise in the number of
central nervous system disorders.
</P>
<P>
By September, they were able to confirm that the patients had
been infected with West Nile fever.
</P>
<P>
After further test of bloods and spinal fluid samples, a total
of 393 patients were confirmed as having the infection in addition
to meningitis and encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which also causes fever, rash, severe aches, eye
irritation and lymph-node involvement, is believed to have been
carried to Europe by migrating birds.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, the West Nile fever virus is normally transmitted by
a special kind of mosquito, birds from Africa may have carried the
virus to Europe and passed it on to mosquitos there.
</P>
<P>
Apartment blocks in urban areas, particularly those which had
experienced flooding, were heavily infested and provide a good
breeding ground for the mosquito.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas of Europe, urban conditions are suitable for the
introduction and amplification of West Nile virus, with the risk
of future epidemics," the researchers warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tunisian Exports to Asian Countries Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Tunisian-Asian trade volume
went up to 1,148 million U.S. dollars in 1997 from 900 million
dollars in 1996, a 27.5 percent increase, according to statistics
of the Tunisian Ministry of Trade revealed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although this accounts for only 7 percent of Tunisia's total
foreign trade, the percentage is growing, said the statistics.
</P>
<P>
The major trade partners of Tunisia among the Asian countries
are Indonesia, Pakistan, Iran, China, Turkey, Malaysia, Japan and
India.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian exports to the Asian markets accounted for 5.8
percent of its total exports in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit, however, increased to 320 million dollars in
1997, compared with 278 million in 1996. The increase is
attributed to the rise of Tunisia's trade deficit with Japan,
which accounts for two thirds of the total trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Among the major exports of Tunisia to the Asian countries are
phosphate and its derivatives, textiles, the products of
mechanical industry and electrical appliances. It imports
processing and elementary materials, foodstuffs such as tea, oil
and plastic materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
