<HEADLINE> Operation Helps More Somalis Regain Eyesight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 4 (Xinhua) -- About 350 Somalis
suffering from eye diseases have received treatment in an
eyesight restoring operation which concluded Friday in the
central town of Beletuein, 300 Km north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Mohamed Dhaqaneh Elmi, the chairman of the local
NGO's consortium in the town, four doctors from Kenya have made
medical consultation in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the activity which lasted for four days, the doctors
have managed to restore the eyesight for 240 people, mainly the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
Elmi who contacted the journalists via VHF radio in Mogadishu
said 220 people were offered free inter-ocular lenses and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Those who got treatment from the Kenyan doctors have mainly
suffered from cataract. There had also been eight patients who
suffered from glaucoma, and six other people who only needed
minor operations.
</P>
<P>
The operation which took place in the main hospital of the
town run by the Italian NGO known as COSV has also attracted many
people from the surrounding districts, regions and villages.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that the doctors from Kenya arrive in
the central town of Beletuein for conducting similar operations.
</P>
<P>
More than 266 people regained their eyesight in March this
year, while another 294 people have benefited from the operation
in June last year.
</P>
<P>
The central town of Bekletuein is one of the most peaceful
areas of the country at the moment where an Islamic court in
collaboration with the local authorities and the business
community of the town is operating to secure the stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
