<HEADLINE> U.N. Protests Against Ethiopian Spy Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
lodged a strong protest with the Ethiopian authorities against
their accusations that some 30 U.N. staff members working in the
country had engaged in espionage activities, U.N. spokesman said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 30 U.N. staff members, of Eritrean and Ethiopian origin,
have been declared "persona non grata" and given them one month,
starting on August 7, to leave the country, Fred Eckhard,
spokesman for the U.N. secretary-general, said.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian authorities accused these U.N. workers, all of
whom had been working at the U.N. complex in the Ethiopian capital
of Addis Ababa, of espionage activities which Ethiopia "deemed
incompatible with the national security interest of the country,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has sent a strong protest to the Ethiopian
authorities, reminding them that "U.N. staff members enjoy
privileges and immunities and are independent officials
responsible for the U.N. secretary-general only," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. also firmly stated that blanket and unsubstantiated
accusations are not acceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. legal office is pursuing the matter with the Ethiopian
authorities while these U.N. workers and their families have been
relocated for their safety, the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
