<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Reports Erratic Arrivals of Foodstuffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The "oil-for-food "
program is now delivering significant quantities of foodstuffs in
Iraq, but erratic arrivals of foodstuffs have unfortunately
continued, a U.N. official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Benon V. Sevan, executive director of the Iraq program, told
the United Nations Security Council that the erratic arrivals of
foodstuffs are caused by late submissions of applicants,
inadequate commercial and financial communications as well as poor
performance by some suppliers on making timely deliveries.
</P>
<P>
Sevan noted the enhanced distribution plan, while increasing
the caloric value of the food basket, is unlikely to lead to any
marked improvement in the quality of foodstuffs distributed and
this would require greater funding at the expense of other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The situation with the medical sector is complex and far from
satisfactory, and the rate of distribution to end users in the
north is low, at just 20 percent, the executive director said,
adding that in the center and south of the country, only 16
percent has reached end users.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. The Security Council adopted a resolution in 1995 which
allowed Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months to buy humanitarian supplies for its people.
</P>
<P>
The council adopted another resolution early this year which
allowed Iraq to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every
six months to ease the further deteriorating humanitarian
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions against Iraq will not be lifted until it is
certified that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction in accordance with relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
