<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Edges Down to 8.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment dropped
by 0.1 percentage points to 8.3 percent in August, the lowest
since August 1990, Statistics Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Employment rose 37,000 in August, bringing gains over the last
two months to 63,000, more than offsetting the losses in May and
June.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, Canada's employment has grown 1.4 percent
compared with a 2.0 percent gain over the same period last year,
the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Full-time employment rose by 42,000 in August while part-time
employment fell by 4,900.
</P>
<P>
Most employment gains were in the service sector, with retail
rising by 20,200 and business and personal services by 19,500.
</P>
<P>
In the goods-producing sector, construction was up 12,700,
after recovering from strikes.
</P>
<P>
Yet, manufacturing fell by 22,600 jobs in August despite the
end of the General Motors strike and following a loss of 34,000
jobs in July. In the resources sector, 12,600 jobs were lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
