<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Cannot Rule out DPRK Satellite Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Friday that it could not rule out a claim by the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea that it launched a scientific satellite
into orbit on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen that report and we are still evaluating the data
connected with the launch and we cannot at this point rule out
that an object was placed in orbit," an intelligence official
said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have said the DPRK test fired a two-stage Taepo
Dong 1 ballistic missile on Monday. But the DPRK Korean Central
News Agency said the launch was of a three-stage, domestically
developed rocket that sent a satellite into orbit.
</P>
<P>
The satellited went into orbit at 0311 GMT on Monday, four
minutes 53 seconds after its launch from the DPRK territory, the
Korean Central News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. intelligence official said that there was a Taepo Dong
1 launched, and Washington could not rule out whether the
ballistic missile put a satellite in orbit.
</P>
<P>
He said agencies throughout the U.S. intelligence community
were reviewing data gathered at the time of the launch to try to
confirm or knock down the DPRK news agancy's report.
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon official still insisted that the DPRK launched a
Taepo Dong missile. Asked how it could be sure, he said: "We
monitor the (Korean) peninsula very closely."
</P>
<P>
The United States expressed concern at the launch earlier this
week, and said it would raise the issue at bilateral talks in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Japan withdrew an offer of talks on establishing diplomatic
relations with the DPRK and ruled out further food aid to the
country after the launch.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea has accused the
United States and Japan of making a "fuss" over the launch.
</P>
<P>
"Some people... are making a fuss, ignorant of this valuable
success of science and technology," the DPRK Foreign Ministry said
in a statement. "They suspected it to be a ballistic missile
launching test, expressed some 'apprehensions' and described it as
a 'serious event.'" 
</P>
</TEXT>
