<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada to Layoff Workers Late Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada is set to lay off
about half of its employees after midnight Friday as there is no
end in sight to a strike by its pilots.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal-based airline is reported to have issued some
layoff notices. The letter said the airline "is forced to take
many difficult steps to minimize the financial impact of the
shutdown."
</P>
<P>
About 11,000 of its 23,000 employees are expected to be laid
off. The first workers to be affected will be flight attendants
and ground crews.
</P>
<P>
The pilots' strike began just before midnight on Tuesday after
talks on wage increases failed between the airline and its 2,100
pilots.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada has cancelled flights at least through Sunday night.
Even if the pilots were to go back to work Friday, it would take
four or five days before services return to normal.
</P>
<P>
Though both sides say they are willing to talk, no such
meetings have been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The airline is estimated to lose about 13 million dollars (8.5
million U.S. dollars) in revenue a day during the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
