<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Higher but of Best Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets ended a
turbulent week with a minor comeback despite a shaky start on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
The European shares started the day optimistically but the
gains were pared back by the end of the day as the Dow slipped
into negative territory.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index remained positive for the most of the
day, jumping up 76.2 points at one time. By close, however, the
FTSE was up 48.3 points at 5167.0.
</P>
<P>
An edgy opening in New York followed heavy losses in the
previous session. Tokyo's Nikkei index also finished heavily down
overnight after the collapse of Toa Steel, the biggest failure of
a manufacturer in the country since World War II.
</P>
<P>
However in Hong Kong the Hang Seng was up 135.59 at 7,454.18 in
late trading, lending some momentum to London.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German stocks advanced but gave up most of their
initial gains, too, after a tepid open on Wall Street and traders
said the rebound was technical.
</P>
<P>
The electronically traded Xetra Dax closed 1.41 percent higher
at 4,864.97 points, while the floor traded DAX advanced 0.17
percent to 4,820.25.
</P>
<P>
Volume was low ahead of a bank-holiday weekend in the United
States which would see markets there closed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There's no news coming out of Russia at the moment and we had
a pretty good sell off over the last few days," one Frankfurt
trader was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"People are afraid of taking a big position when something
could happen over the long weekend. That's going to keep a lot of
speculators out of the market," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's failure to break out of its funk in opening trade
let the air out of a rally in German shares that took the Dax as
high as 4,953.49 points. By the German close, the Dow was hardly
changed at 7,681.45 points.
</P>
<P>
But German shares were bolstered by overnight comments from
Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer, who in remarks to journalists
late Thursday, said interest rate cuts were not the answer to
world market tensions and that economic growth was not a problem
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Russian financial crisis would not lead to a
crisis among German banks, which have more exposure to Russia than
many of their European counterparts.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the bourse chalked up a gain as the Cac 40 index
finished the day and week at 3,690.75 points, up 1.21 percent from
the Thursday close.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
