<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Has Right to Determine Own Destiny: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban people have
the right to determine their own destiny and sanctions against
them are anathema, South African President Nelson Mandela said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Democratic South Africa is proud to be amongst the majority
of nations who affirm the right to the Cuban people to determine
their own destiny, " Mandela said at a banquet in honor of Cuban
President Fidel Castro in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions which seek to punish them for having decided to do
so are anathema to the international order to which we aspire,"
said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He was obviously referring to the economic sanctions imposed
against Cuba by the United States since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela thanked the Cuban people for their
support during the apartheid years.
</P>
<P>
"If today all South Africans enjoy the rights of democracy, if
they are able at last to address the grinding poverty of a system
that denied them even the most basic amenities of life, it is
also because of Cuba's selfless support for the struggle to free
all of South Africa's people and the countries of our region from
the inhumane and destructive system of apartheid."
</P>
<P>
As a sign of gratitude, Castro was awarded with South Africa's
highest civilian honor for foreigners, the Order of Good Hope.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, now chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM),
called on Cuba to work together with South Africa on the
empowerment of poorer nations.
</P>
<P>
"The achievement of our shared goals depends ultimately on our
success, in concert with others, in placing the interests and
needs of developing countries at the top of the world agenda, and
in promoting a reform of international systems and institutions
in conformity with democratic principles."
</P>
<P>
Castro, who attended the NAM summit in Durban, began his
two-day state visit to South Africa Friday.
</P>
<P>
He was given a full-ceremonial welcome by Mandela Friday
morning in Cape Town and described by Mandela as "one of my
greatest friends."
</P>
<P>
Later, Castro addressed a joint sitting of parliament and
visited Robben Island where Mandela had been jailed in the trying
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
