<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Arrange Repatriation of Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government
is making arrangements to repatriate some 800 rebels in western
Liberia and bring them home to participate in the country's
rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted Sierra Leonean Deputy Defense
Minister Hinga Norman as saying Friday that "we have been
informed of their presence and an arrangement is being made by
government and my ministry to bring them back."
</P>
<P>
According to Norman, rebel soldiers have told authorities in
western Liberia that they were tired of fighting and wanted to go
home.
</P>
<P>
This is a good intention which should be encouraged, the
minister noted, adding that they should be given a chance to
participate in the government's demobilization, disarmament and
rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
Following the collapse of a military junta last February, many
rebel soldiers have continued their fighting in some parts of the
tiny west African country with rear bases allegedly being in
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a large number of child combatants who
have defected from the junta in western Liberia have also
expressed their desire to return to Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
