<HEADLINE> Authorities Warn of Rising Crime in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Two senior Russian officials on
Friday warned of rising crimes in the wake of the country's
worsening financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of the Federal Security Service Vladimir Putin
and Acting Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin gave the warning at
a meeting of the Federation Council, or upper house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Putin attributed the mounting crimes to slump production, high
unemployment, rising social tension and the huge gap between the
haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
Putin also expressed alarm over the huge number of
organizations that seek protection by resorting to guard services.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, the interior chief, said Russia faces a new outburst
of crimes in the face of the financial crisis, but his ministry
lacks money to operate effectively.
</P>
<P>
"The state has to pay a high price for the poor police," he
warned, noting that money allocated to the ministry was barely
enough to pay salaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
