<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Military Helicopters Crash in Nevada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Air Force
helicopters crashed in the desert near outskirts of Las Vegas,
capital of Nevada, early Friday morning, according to reports
reaching here later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Military officials said 12 people were on the helicopters, but
the fate of them was not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman at Nellis Air Force Base on the outskirts of Las
Vegas said emergency crews were making their way to the site of
the crash, in rugged desert mountains about 80 kilometers north of
the base.
</P>
<P>
The two HH-60G helicopters collided and crashed about 1 a.m.
during a training exercise in which the crews were using
night-vision goggles, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force said it has 99 HH-60G helicopters in use at 12
bases in the United States and abroad, adding that the Nellis
helicopters were part of the 66th Rescue Squadron, the Air Force's
largest rescue squadron.
</P>
<P>
Until Friday's crash, the Air Force had 21 major aviation
accidents this fiscal year, with "major" defined as causing a
death or one million U.S. dollar damage, according to military
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
