<HEADLINE> American Jones Shares Million Dollars IAAF Jackpot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 5 (Xinhua) -- American Marion Jones won her
100 meters title here on Saturday, becoming one of three athletes
to share the one million dollars IAAF jackpot at stake.
</P>
<P>
The American beat her slow start to clock in 10.83 seconds,
beating runner-up Sevatheda Fynes by more than a quarter-second.
</P>
<P>
The victory gave Jones a third of the 1 million Golden League
jackpot, in addition to 200,000 dollars for the women's overall
Grand Prix title and 50,000 for the race win.
</P>
<P>
Jones got another 50,000 for taking the long jump with a top
leap of 7.13 meters.
</P>
<P>
So far, Jones has won all 35 events she entered in 1998, which
includes 60- and 200-meter races.
</P>
<P>
Jones split the jackpot, a bonus for athletes who win their
events at all six Golden League meets plus the GP Finals, with
Hicham El Guerrouj and Haile Gebrselassie, who also stayed
unbeaten for the year with dominating wins.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Morocco's El Guerrouj ran alone for the final lap of
the 1,500 meters in clocking 3 minutes and 32.03 seconds, and
Gebrselassie also had little trouble in capturing the 3,000
meters in a relatively slow 7:50.00.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Moscow Grand Prix, the only other person in
contention for the big prize was Bryan Bronson, but the American
finished in a miserable sixth in the 400 hurdles which was won by
world champion Stephane Diagana of France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
