<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Hit by Heaviest Floods Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese government has urged
provincial authorities to rescue people hit by heaviest floods
ever in history.
</P>
<P>
The violent floods caused by torrential rains are sweeping a
number of northern provinces particularly Kassala, the Northern,
and the River Nile provinces.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Minister of Interior Abdel-Raheem Mohamed Hussein
was quoted by the local daily Al-Ra'i Al-Aam Saturday as saying
that the floods that hit the Northern Province resulted in damages
amounting to 46 billion Sudanese pounds (about 23 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He estimated that some 30,000 families have lost their homes
and belongings.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Federal Ruling Divan said that an aircraft
carrying relief materials and medicines had left for the Northern
province where the flood had made 12,000 families homeless.
</P>
<P>
The province is expected to witness further higher levels of
the Nile water that have already exceeded all the previous
records.
</P>
<P>
The International Association of the Red Cross and the
International Association of the Red Crescent appealed earlier for
relief materials to the flood-stricken people in north and
east Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
