<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Minister to Visit Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini will arrive here Tuesday for talks on the Mideast
peace process and the Egypt-European Union partnership agreement.
</P>
<P>
Dini will pay a two-day visit, during which he is expected to
discuss with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa ways of reviving
the Mideast peace process, Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister for
European Affairs Fathi el Shazli told Egypt's Middle East News Agency
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israelis have been
stalled since March 1997 after Israel began construction of a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. The talks are currently
stuck over the overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Syria and Lebanon, on the one hand,
and Israel, on the other, came to a standstill in early 1996 due
to disputes over the future of the Golan Heights Israel captured
from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
European Union members, including Italy, are keen on helping
advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Dini will also touch on other regional issues in
Europe, the Middle East and Africa, the Egyptian official said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers will review the progress made in the efforts
to reach the long-expected Egypt-European Union partnership
agreement, he added.
</P>
<P>
A cooperation and coordination agreement between the foreign
ministries of the two countries is expected to be concluded at the
end of Dini's visit, Shazli said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
