<HEADLINE> Gebrselassie Wins Moscow GP Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia
clocked in a relative slow timing of 7:50.00, but was enough to
win the 3,000 meters to guarantee a share of the one million
dollars jackpot at the IAAF Grand Prix finals here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In his discipline, Gebrselassie had little trouble to capture
the title at the Luzhniki Olympic Stadium as his closest rival
Luke Kipkosgei finished in 7:50.87.
</P>
<P>
So far, Gebrselassie has had 20 straight outdoor wins with two
world records set in the 5,000 and 10,000 meters within a
two-week span in June.
</P>
<P>
Early, Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco, won the 1,500 meters in
three minutes 32.03 seconds, becoming the first athlete to
guarantee a share of the one million dollars bonus.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Gebrselassie and Guerrouj, the other only candidate
who can claim a share of the IAAF Grand Prix jackpot was American
Marion Jones who was to compete in the women's 100-meters later
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The jackpot is for athletes who win their events at all six
Golden League meets plus the Grand Prix Final.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Moscow Grand Prix, the only other person in
contention for the big prize was Bryan Bronson, but the American
was beaten to the sixth place in the 400 hurdles by world
champion France's Stephane Diagana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
