<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Paddlers to Clean-Sweep Chinese Grand Prix Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Earlier top seed and world number 3 Wang Nan overcame a fierce
surge from seventh seed Sun Jin to win the women's singles title
in an all-Chinese final.
</P>
<P>
The men's doubles trophy went to Chinese tandem Ma Lin and Qin
Zhijian, who beat compatriots Wang Liqin and Yan Sen 21-16, 21-15.
</P>
<P>
For the non-Chinese players, the only hope to stop the hosts
from a cleansweep lies in the women's doubles event, which has
five non-Chinese pairs in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Kong Linghui, who won the Australian Grand Prix last
week , suffered a surprise exit in the quarterfinals to rising
star Ma Lin 21-15, 18-21, 21-19, 15-21, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
In the other men's singles matches, Olympic champion Liu
Guoliang demolished C. Legout of France 21-11, 21-16, 21-19. Wang
Liqin trounced K. Kreanga of Greece 21-12, 21-14, 21-8, and Yan
Sen anchored the cleansweep by edging out W. Schlager of Austria
21-13, 21-16, 15-21. 19-21. 21-11.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who plays a left-handed topspin game in the handshake
grip, overpowered Sun in the first two sets 21-12, 21-12. But the
18-year-old Sun, who had beat Wang in the Japanese Grand Prix
early this year, fought back to level the score at 8-8 in the t
hird.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Wang, world silver medallist and World Cup
winner, used her stunning speed and spin to go ahead 20-17 for
three match points, only to be denied by Sun with powerful
forehand attacks.
</P>
<P>
But Wang, who won the Chinese Grand Prix in 1995, grasped the
last chance when Sun took advantage at 21-20, putting it 21-all
before winning two points in a row for the title.
</P>
<P>
"I have been under tough pressure before the match beacuse Sun
beat me this year in Japan," Wang said. "I'm very happy to win
the Chinese Grand Prix for the second time."
</P>
<P>
The victory earned her 8,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Wu Na, who dropped to Wang in the semifinals
earlier, finished joint third with fellow Chinese Zhang Hui, a
loser at the hands of Sun.
</P>
<P>
The men's doubles final was also an all-Chinese affair, with
Ma Lin and Qin Zhijian defeating Wang Liqin and Yan Sen 21-16,
21-15 to take the trophy.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Liu Guoliang who paired with former Olympic
champion and world NO.3 Kong Linghui shared the third place with
Feng Zhe and Zhang Yong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
