<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Declares War Against Family Violence (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese, who used to regard
wife-beating as something common and normal, are becoming
increasingly concerned about family violence and trying every
means to curb it, an official with the All-China Women's
Federation (ACWF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ding Lu, deputy director of the Women's Rights and Interests
Department of the ACWF, said that only a dozen years ago many
Chinese thought problems like husbands beating their wives were
"purely family business" that shouldn't be interfered with either
by the government or the law.
</P>
<P>
"They refused to call it a 'social problem,' and held that
mediation efforts of kind neighbors or community officials would
be enough to solve it," she added.
</P>
<P>
In today's China, however, more and more people are talking
about and openly condemning family violence, while local
governments and judicial organs are taking active steps toward
punishment, Ding said.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that Chinese society is becoming more civilized
and progressive," she said, citing the example of central China's
Hunan Province, where special regulations against family violence
were formulated after a man threw his wife from a tall building.
</P>
<P>
Because of the regulations, she said, a county-level leading
official was ousted from his post for the ill-treatment of his
wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Declares War Against Family Violence (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In major cities like Beijing and Shanghai, hot lines and
emergency aid centers have been opened for victims of family
violence, who also receive support from the local news media.
</P>
<P>
However, Ding conceded that in recent years reports of family
violence have constantly increased despite social efforts.
</P>
<P>
A main reason lies in the lingering feudal concept of women's
inferiority to men, which has been deeply rooted in the minds of
many male Chinese, including quite a few urban intellectuals and
officials, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she said, Chinese society and the economy are in a
changing and transitional period, and many families have lost
their peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
For example, she said, family violence is apparently on the
rise in the homes of workers laid off from state-owned
enterprises, especially when the wives also have lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
There are also many cases of family violence resulting from
extra-marital affairs, which is a relatively new source of
violence for Chinese families, she added.
</P>
<P>
Many people across the country are now urging the state
legislature to formulate a special law against family violence,
said Ding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
