<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Vows to Support Irish Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Saturday his country would never turn away from the Irish
people.
</P>
<P>
He promised that "America will be there every step of the way"
to the path of peace," according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
"The demons of the past are losing their power to divide you,"
Clinton said to thousands of people in Ireland's western town of
Limerick after he was honored by nine Irish universities for
trying to end three decades of violence in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"This peace is yours, yours and no one else's. All the leaders
in the world, all the speeches in the world would not have
amounted to a hill of beans if you had not gone out and voted
Yes," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"This is you at your best. Do not let them break your will,"
said Clinton, who on Thursday toured Northern Ireland to offer
words of resolve and encouragement in Belfast, Omagh and Armagh.
</P>
<P>
But he also cautioned that the "enemies of peace" would try to
take away the hopeful future.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will wind up his three-day visit to Northern Ireland
and the Irish Republic and head back to Washington later Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
