<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana to Host Pan-African Conference on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A Pan-African conference on how
indigenous and tropical forest dwellers of sub-Saharan Africa
could be protected from the hazards of modern development will be
held in Ghanaian capital Accra on September 7 to 12.
</P>
<P>
A Pan-African News Agency report from Accra said the
conference is being organized by the London-based International
Alliance of Indigenous and Tribal Peoples of the Tropical Forests
(IAITPTF) in collaboration with the Green Earth Organization of
Ghana and other multilateral bodies.
</P>
<P>
Seventy private and public sector environmental experts and
journalists from the sub-region would attend the conference under
the theme of "Indigenous People, Forest Dependent Communities and
Biodiversity," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The conference will seek to harmonize indigenous culture and
industrial activity, forest preservation and industrialization,
ethnic and foreign religions, it added.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Ilenre, Secretary-General of IAITPTF, told journalists
in Accra that the conference is meant to provide African
non-governmental organizations with a single document "to serve
as a reference point in our international negotiations on issues
concerning our indigenous people."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the activities of timber merchants, miners,
ivory tusk hunters and industrialists in Africa are carried out
without supervision because most African do not have definite
policies regarding preservation and the interest of indigenous
people.
</P>
<P>
"Most African countries are yet to adopt definite policies on
forest preservation and indigenous people's interest though they
feel deeply concerned about issues affecting indigenous people
and poverty alleviation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference will seek to revive African indigenous cultures
and other ethnic rules mean to protect the forest and its
dwellers, which have been relegated to the background as
primitive, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
