<HEADLINE> Victoria Falls Talks to Focus on Ceasefire: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe said Saturday that Monday's peace summit on the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) will focus on spearheading a
ceasefire and the withdrawal of allied forces from the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in the Zimbabwean resort town of Victoria Falls
was proposed by Mugabe during the 12th Non-Aligned Movement
summit in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting a delegation of DRC doctors, Mugabe
said the achievement of peace in the Congo would facilitate the
withdrawal of allied (Zimbabwean, Angolan and Namibian) forces.
</P>
<P>
"When we met in Durban, we agreed that the objective of peace
was paramount," Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Mugabe as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said there was no need to continue the war in Congo
because forces from both sides no longer wanted to continue
fighting.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces were sent in to help DRC President Laurent
Kabila, who accused Uganda and Rwanda of invading his country by
backing rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean government officials said they were still not sure
if Kabila would be present at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from the DRC say the rebel leaders and the
Kabila government still had to decide whether they would
participate in the Victoria Falls meeting.
</P>
<P>
Angola and Namibia have been invited to the Victoria Falls.
</P>
</TEXT>
