<HEADLINE> Dhaka Hosts Seminar on Investment in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Participants at a regional
seminar here on Saturday called for solid political leadership in
South Asian countries to help the region face the challenges and
take advantage of the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
They also called for necessary reform measures in key sectors
of these countries and removing all bureaucrat barriers at the
one-day seminar on "Investment in South Asia," organized by the
Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industries and
attended by ministers, former ministers, chamber leaders,
businessmen and leading economists.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the seminar, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina proposed
an Asian energy grid to energize economic activities in the
region.
</P>
<P>
All the South Asian countries should enact substantive and
meaningful changes in their investment and import and export trade
laws, considering the ongoing globalization process, she said.
</P>
<P>
Terming investment the most crucial factor that promotes
growth, she said, "We need a big push in level of investment to
accelerate growth in Bangladesh."
</P>
<P>
She invited foreign investors to invest in Bangladesh to
utilize the country's huge natural and human resources as well as
its vast market here, as the government has relaxed various
restrictions earlier imposed on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Listing available potentialities for South Asia's rapid growth,
the prime minister said if enormous market, huge untapped natural
resources and human resources were harnessed properly, it would be
easy to convert this region into one of the most prosperous in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Describing globalization both as a challenge and as an
opportunity, Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed urged
all countries of the region to integrate their economies with the
globalization process in the interest of the people of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
There should be an in-built confidence among countries of South
Asia, as "we all should try together to benefit ourselves from the
on-going globalization process through ensuring our access to the
world market," he pointed out. 
</P>
