<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 370 Eritreans Leave Ethiopia for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The office of Ethiopian
government spokesman announced Saturday that a total of 370
Eritreans will be leaving for home Saturday to rejoin family
members who have been deported for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Saturday, the office said the 370
Eritreans are being accompanied by the International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC).
</P>
<P>
"When individuals are asked to leave the country, their
families are encouraged to join them and the 370 who are leaving
today have chosen to do so," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government, emanating from its right and
responsibility to guarantee the safety and security of its
citizens, has taken measures to deport "certain categories of
Eritreans" for national security reasons after thorough
investigation of each case, it added.
</P>
<P>
The deportees include Eritreans who were gathering
information, those who were involved in acts of spying against
the security, defense and economic interests of Ethiopia, those
who were organizing and running a covert Eritrean People's
Liberation Front (EPLF) party structure and those donating or
soliciting funds to help the Eritrean regime in its war of
aggression against Ethiopia, according to the office.
</P>
<P>
"The Ethiopian government carries out these deportations in
full observance of international human rights laws and standards
and follows the appropriate due process," the office said, adding
that "the government deports only when it has concrete evidence
that a person has committed acts which fall into one of the above
categories."
</P>
<P>
Eritrea says up to 17,000 of its nationals have been expelled
from Ethiopia since a border dispute between the two countries
erupted in May. But Ethiopia says those deported for security
reasons were only around 4,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
