<HEADLINE> Iranian President Condemns Assault on Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami condemned Saturday hardliners' assault on two senior
government officials, calling on the relevant authorities to
seriously deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
Khatami was reacting in a statement to the Friday attacks by a
group of hardliners on Vice President for Development and Social
Affairs Abdollah Nouri and Minister of Culture and Islamic
Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani attending funeral ceremony for 700
soldiers killed in the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq War.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the information and interior ministries to take
necessary measures to deal with such willful acts and ugly
violence and behavior and the elements attacking Mr. Nouri and
Mr. Mohajerani," Khatami said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the authorities should show little tolerance to "the
ugly acts of a few who adamantly oppose institutionalization of
laws in the society and prevalence of freedom and justice, and the
lawbreakers who for being ignorant or having certain motives only
understand language of force."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president also called on the judiciary to cooperate
with the relevant authorities to pursue the case.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran's State Expediency Council, the powerful
arbitrary and advisory body, also condemned Saturday the assault
and called on relevant authorities to pursue the case and
prosecute those responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Nouri and Mohajerani are key figures of the government of
moderate Khatami and main advocates for Khatami's policies on
social freedom and reforms. They have been at odds with the
hardliners who oppose Khatami's policies.
</P>
<P>
Nouri was ousted as Interior Minister by the conservative
Majlis in June in an impeachment motion and Mohajerani, also
government spokesman, has been sharply criticized by the
conservatives for his efforts to push press freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
