<HEADLINE> Flood-Control Official Cautions Against Laxity as Waters Recede </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the State
Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters has again cautioned
against possible laxity in vigilance as floodwaters recede and
stressed there should be no "trusting to luck."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, the official said the two-month
battle against floods has entered the final stage. The primary
task now is to ensure against levee breaches or collapses during
the retreat of floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Levees in many sections along the Yangtze, Nenjiang and Songhua
rivers have been weakened by long exposure to water and that
people working on the levees are also weary.
</P>
<P>
"With the coming of autumn winds, the risk of dike slides and
collapse is higher," the official said. "In serious cases, they
can cause levee breaches."
</P>
<P>
He cited many such cases in the last 40 years to illustrate the
danger. The most recent happened in 1996 in Yueyang City in Hunan
Province where the retreating water brought down a section of
dike, causing heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
"We should learn from historical lessons and avoid making the
same errors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should not drop vigilance and leave things to
chance. Instead, we should have a proper assessment of the flood
situation, continue 24-hour patrolling on the levees and check on,
and reinforce, danger spots to ensure ultimate success," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
