<HEADLINE> Malaysian Opposition Leader Seeks Emergency Parliament Sitting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian opposition
leader Lim Kit Siang Saturday called for an emergency sitting of
Parliament to discuss the dismissal of Anwar Ibrahim as deputy
prime minister and finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Lim, who is Democratic Action Party Secretary-General, also
sought a meeting with Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad to discuss
what he described as a "crisis" following Anwar's firing.
</P>
<P>
Lim also called for the setting up of a royal commission of
inquiry to investigate the allegations made against Anwar.
</P>
<P>
"It should also investigate equally serious allegation by Anwar
that instruments of government have been manipulated in a
political conspiracy to topple him," Lim was quoted by Malaysia's
national news agency Bernama as telling reporters after meeting
Anwar at the latter's house here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lim said, "It is not a matter concerning a personality. It is a
matter concerning the nation with far-reaching political economic
and social implications. I'm not here to defend Anwar."
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as deputy prime minister and finance minister
of the country on Wednesday without official reasons given.
</P>
<P>
However, there are serious allegations of sexual impropriety
and other possible crimes against him as mentioned in the book "50
Dalil Mengapa Anwar tidak Boleh Jadi PM" (50 Reasons Why Anwar
Cannot Become PM).
</P>
<P>
Anwar denied the allegations and said he was the victim of a
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was also expelled from the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) by the UMNO Supreme Council early Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
