<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates to Women's Congress Object to "Periodic Employment" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Periodic employment of women
will violate the legal principle that men and women have equal
rights to work and degrade women's social and family status,
according to some delegates to the Eighth National Congress of
Chinese Women.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Women's Federation (ACWF) has discouraged the
central government from making any policies on periodic employment
in the current social stage, said Ding Lu, deputy-director of the
Department of Women's Rights and Interests of ACWF.
</P>
<P>
Under "periodic employment," women would stop working for a
period of time after their marriage or delivery and then be
allowed to begin work several years later when their babies have
grown up, Ding explained, adding that it is groundless to say that
this kind of employment system will help relieve the competition
for jobs and reduce under-employment.
</P>
<P>
She said the large population of women employees is not the
major cause for the increasing number of under-employed and
laid-off people. The problem has been brought on by social and
economic reforms during the transitional period, she said.
</P>
<P>
Staying away from work for a long period of time will cause
financial difficulties for a considerable number of families and
can weaken the competitiveness of both skilled female laborers and
intellectual workers, and make it difficult for them to find a job
when they want to resume work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates to Women's Congress Object to "Periodic Employment" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The suspended working period would also mean fewer
opportunities for promotion for females, Ding said.
</P>
<P>
Some elderly delegates, who have engaged in women's work for
many years, said they have been striving to liberate women from
being confined to household work, and to obtain better political
and economic status by involving them in social life. But periodic
employment might bring women back to their families and, in turn,
lower their status in society and the family.
</P>
<P>
The government should not impose periodic employment on women
just because they have an indispensable role in reproduction, said
Professor Tan Lin, an expert in female population from Nankai
University in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Both men and women should take the responsibility for raising
children and doing household work, Tan said. The reality in China
has also proved that many families with newborn babies can find a
way to enable young mothers to work.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls among women conducted by the ACWF show that the
majority of women do not like the idea of periodic employment, Tan
said.
</P>
<P>
The government should respect women's own wills in employment
and should not issue any policies to regulate them, Ding
said. Women in some well-off families may choose periodic
employment, while in many ordinary families the loss of a woman's
job could lead to financial problems.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government of Shanghai decided long ago not to
issue a policy on "periodic employment," said Li Li, an official
with the city's women's federation.
</P>
<P>
One of the reasons is that surveys conducted by the federation
found most of the local women would not accept the policy when
told that, under the periodic employment system, they would have
to find new jobs after staying away from work for a comparatively
long period of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0094 </DOCNO>
