<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Bans Forest Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- An area of 4.6 million
hectares of primitive forest in the western part of southwest
China's Sichuan Province will be protected from lumbering because
of forest-logging ban issued earlier this month, according to
today's Overseas Edition of "People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
The region, a fountainhead of tributes to the Yangtze River,
China's largest, includes 57 counties and 3.7 million hectares of
shrubbery.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
more than 70 lumber mills here have provided 120 million cubic
meters of commercial timber for the country and contributed two
billion yuan to the state in taxes.
</P>
<P>
However, environmentalists say that over-logging has diminished
the coverage of primitive forest, resulting in serious
desertification of grassland and soil erosion on the upper reaches
of the Yangtze. The area that has experienced soil erosion has
expanded from 60,000 square kilometers in the 1950s to 110,000
today.
</P>
<P>
The shrinking forest area has posed a threat to the life of
rare wildlife such as the giant panda and also to the gigantic
Three Gorges water conservation project. Silt brought to the Three
Gorges by the Chuanjiang River alone amounts to 600 million tons a
year.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has implemented the ban, which is a part of China's
largest forest-conservation program from now into the next
century. The ban includes protection of forest resources in
Heilongjiang, Jilin and Sichuan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the province will shut down local timber
exchanges, use electricity and coal as substitutes for wood fuel
and allow consumption of fuel forest only for rural living.
</P>
<P>
Among 45,600 lumberjacks employed by the forest industry here,
24,700 will turn into forest-tenders and 13,400 tree-planters. The
rest will shift to other businesses.
</P>
<P>
As lumberjacks turn into tree planters, an area of 1.08 million
hectares of forest is expected in the area by 2010, an increase in
the local forest coverage from the current 19.4 percent to 23
percent.
</P>
<P>
The project will also substantially treat the soil erosion
problem in the Yangtze River Basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0096 </DOCNO>
