<HEADLINE> Cambodia Still in Deadlock on Forming Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The term of the current
parliament and government of Cambodia will both expire on
September 24, but the three major parties remain in deadlock on
forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
A three-day meeting aimed to boost political reconciliation in
Cambodia opened in Siem Reap Saturday, but failed to yield any
concrete results when the first-day session ended.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk, who hosted the meeting, has been calling
on the three major political parties to make some compromise.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the three main political parties --
Cambodian People's Party (CPP), Funcinpec and the Sam Rainsy Party
(SRP) as well as the National Election Committee and the
Constitutional Council participated in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy, the three top party leaders,
did not attend the meeting as the King hoped.
</P>
<P>
None of the three parties were ready to make concession at the
first-day session.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won 64 of the 122 Assembly seats in the July 26 general
elections, but failed to obtain the two-thirds majority required
to form the new government on its own.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has invited Funcinpec and the SRP, which won 43 and 15
seats respectively in the election, to form a coalition
government, but were declined by the two parties, which rejected
as untrue the results of the election.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and SRP alleged that there were irregularities in the
election and demanded recounting and re-polling in some area.
</P>
<P>
The King has released a message stating the three purposes of
the Siem Reap meeting as restoring order and peace in Phnom Penh,
making it possible to convene the first National Assembly session
and making it functioning normally, and forming the new government.
</P>
<P>
But the King was pessimistic about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I do not have much hope that the three-day meeting will have
the positive result that I wish," the King said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The parties have deep conflicts with each other and have not
yet agreed to make any concessions or compromises." he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
