<HEADLINE> India to Test-fire Longer-range Agni Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- India has decided to
test-fire its new longer-range version of the intermediate range
ballistic missile Agni in the coming weeks, Defence Minister
George Fernandes said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Test firing of Agni-II is inevitable...It will be done soon
but no date had been finalized," Fernandes told the Press Trust
of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times daily reported Saturday that the decision
to conduct the missile test had been taken following the fourth
round of talks between India and the United States last month in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted high-placed Defense Ministry sources as saying
the political decision to go ahead with the tests had been taken
in the light of the perception of the Indian government led by the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) that the international fallout from
its nuclear tests in May has been contained and diplomatically
managed.
</P>
<P>
The Indian defense establishment feels that Washington has only
opposed the deployment of missiles and not per se New Delhi's
missile development program.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes said that the new versions of the missile would use
state-of-the-art technologies developed indigenously.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to give details about the missile's
various dimensions and parameters.
</P>
<P>
Indian media reported Saturday that the missile would be
test-fired over a range of 1,400 kilometers, an advance of nearly
700 kilometers over the previous versions.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the delivery system on the anvil is reported to have
the potential to strike targets more than 2,500 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with PTI, Fernandes admitted that India had
begun developing Sagarika, a missile which can be launched from a
ship or a submarine.
</P>
<P>
The Indian defense minister informed the Consultative Committee
under his ministry of the government approval of the longer-ranged
Agni, which use the same state-of-the-art re-entry technology of
the earlier tested intermediate range ballistic missile 
</P>
</TEXT>
