<HEADLINE> International Rice Conference Due in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The world's major rice producing
states will convene in Cairo on Monday to discuss ways of boosting
rice production and promoting global cooperation in this field.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 61 major rice producing countries will attend
the three-day 19th session of the International Rice Commission
(IRC) under the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United
Nations (FAO), said a news release faxed to Xinhua by FAO's Near
East Regional Office Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The release said the participants would mainly tackle the
challenges and opportunities in sustainable rice production and
post-production, global technology innovation and cooperation in
rice production.
</P>
<P>
Rice is one of the most important staple foods in the
world. Over 50 percent of the world's population depend upon rice
for about 80 percent of their food needs, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent of the global output of rice is produced and
consumed in developing countries, it added.
</P>
<P>
The FAO estimated that the 1997 world paddy rice production
hit a record 572 million tonnes, a rise of 2 million tonnes from
the previous record in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It said the global rice trade in 1997 dropped to 18.4 million
tonnes, 1.2 million tonnes less than that in 1996 and 2.5 million
tonnes less than the 1995's record level.
</P>
<P>
The IRC was set up at the fourth FAO Conference in 1948 against
the backdrop of an imminent worldwide food shortage. It was aimed
at promoting cooperative actions by member countries in matters
relating to the production, conservation, distribution, and
consumption of rice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
