<HEADLINE> Registration Ends for Iran's Experts Assembly Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 396 candidates have
registered for the election of Iran's Experts Assembly which
determines the country's supreme leader, local daily Zan (Women)
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The battle for the control of the powerful body between the
moderate and conservative camps is expected to intensify as the
elections date, set on October 23, is nearing.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since the formation of the Experts Assembly
in 1983, nine women registered for the election.
</P>
<P>
President Mohammad Khatami, a leading figure in the left-wing
Society of Combatant Clergymen (SCC), has said he has no intention
to run for the election.
</P>
<P>
But the majority of the SCC, the largest political gathering of
the left wing, have registered for the elections, showing the
group's "great interest" in running for the Experts Assembly which
has been so far dominated by the hardline conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Zan quoted the elections chief and Deputy Interior Minister
Mostafa Tajzadeh as saying that the conservative Guardians Council
would start to review the qualifications of the candidates for the
election.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, candidates for the Experts Assembly
should have qualified knowledge of Islamic jurisprudence as well
as exact conception and interpretation of the Islamic laws.
</P>
<P>
During the past months, leftwing groups accused the Guardians
Council of rejecting moderate candidates in the past elections and
called for revoking the council's right to review the candidates'
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
The left wing expressed great concern that the Guardians
Council may once again reject moderate candidates as part of its
efforts to consolidate the conservatives' hold on the Experts
Assembly. 
</P>
