<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Come to No Remedy for Spreading Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The talks between U.S.
and Japanese finance ministers ended Friday night in San Francisco
without coming to any fresh idea to deal with the jittery global
markets, said reports from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Japanese Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa met for about one and a half hour before
holding separate news briefings in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Both admitted that they had essentially spent the discussion
repeating the previous positions held by the respective side.
</P>
<P>
Japan has pledged that it will implement a program of tax cuts
and increased government spending and will push the Japanese
parliament to enact bills to deal with massive bad loans weighing
down the banking system.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States thinks these measures are not quick
and strong enough, given the importance of the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the revival of Japan's economy is key to put
the global economy back on a sound footing, but he heard no new
proposals from Japan during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held at a time when global financial markets
just ended a turbulent week, mainly as a result of the chain
impact produced by the Asian Crisis, which erupted in July, 1997,
and the recent collapse of the Russian ruble.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial, a main indicator for the world
financial situation, finished 41.97 lower to 7,640.25 on
Friday, losing 411.43 points for the past five sessions.
</P>
<P>
The Dow is now about 1,700 points, or about 18 percent, below
the July 17 record of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
After the briefings, Rubin and Miyazawa were joined for dinner
by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the University of California-Berkeley earlier
Friday, Greenspan said that the U.S. economy may be hurt by
international market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"It is just not credible that the United States can remain an
oasis of prosperity unaffected by a world that is experiencing
greatly increased stress," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his first comment on recent tumbling stock prices, Greenspan
said that the U.S. central bank now saw a balance of risks facing
the country's economy between deflationary pressure from
international crisis, and domestic inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
