<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's 1st Anti-Flood Law Effective in Flood Fighting (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A coal-laden vessel was help
up by flood-control officials from Jiujiang during its voyage on
the Yangtze River on August 7, the day floodwaters teared open a
60 meter-long breach on the levee.
</P>
<P>
"Under the Law on Flood Control, the anti-flood headquarters
has been empowered to use anything possible within reach for the
anti-flood purpose under the state of emergency," said one of
the officials, upon noticing that the captain's reluctance.
</P>
<P>
The captain was asured that all his losses will be compensated
by the government under the law.
</P>
<P>
Today, one month after the vessel was used to fill up the
breach, locals hailed it as a "Meritorious Vessel" and proposed
that it be exhibited in the present position for ever as a witness
for the anti-flooding battles in this city of east China's Jiangxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Of course, Chinese law-makers are no prophets. When they passed
the Flood Control Law last fall, they were by no mean to forecast
that the seasonal floods in 1998 would be the worst flooding after
1954. The law came into force on January 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi Province became the first to benefit from the law by
declaring a state of emergency among all flood-stricken areas this
summer. When the provincial flood-control headquarters ordered the
city government of Fengcheng to provide flood-fighters with
sandbags immediately, Fengcheng did it without any delay.
</P>
<P>
"We might have parleyed for a good price in the past," says a
Fengcheng official, "but we dared not to do so this time, only
because of the enactment of the law."
</P>
<P>
Anhui, Jiangsu and Hubei provinces along the Yangtze, and a
number of cities in China's northernmost Helongjiang Province,
also declared a state of emergency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's 1st Anti-Flood Law Powerful in Flood Fighting (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A series of diversion programs were prepared or carried out in
different places during flood crests. And No one was killed in all
these well and meticulously planned diversions, including the one
in defense of the Daqing Oilfield, the largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, local officials at all levels were made
responsible for a certain section of major river embankments and
lake levees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local governments in flooded areas had torn down a
large number of illegally-built makeshifts or simple houses that
might come in flooding way. "With the law in force, the clear-ups
have become much easier this year," said a local official in
Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
Since August 1, Anhui Provincial authorities imposed traffic
control on navigation over the local section of the Yangtze so to
keep off waves caused by cruising boats against the dykes and
embankments. And all the crews in 600 vessels have observed the
order over the past five weeks,.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, who took over as chairmanship of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress in Spring this year,
has been among the most arduous advocates of the law.
</P>
<P>
In his phone-calls to leaders of localities, the top lawmaker
made frequent reference to the law, urging localities to implement
it in real earnest during the course of flood fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many local officials have reportedly been brought to
justice for violation of the law. In Yueyang City, Hunan Province,
53 officials were disciplined for malfeasance; whereas in
Nanchang, the provincial capital of Jiangxi, three officials were
detained for dereliction of duty in patroling along the dikes.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
