<HEADLINE> Congress Ready to Form Alternative Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- India's opposition Congress
party said it was ready to form an alternative government in the
event of the fall of the government led by the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP), local newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day conclave of senior Congress leaders Friday
in Panchmari, a hill resort in central Madhya Pradesh, Congress
President Sonia Gandhi said: "If and when the need arises, our
party will fulfill its constitutional obligation without
hesitation and provide stability and progress."
</P>
<P>
Sonia mounted a scathing attack on the BJP-led government for
its "all-round failure", saying that the economy was stagnant,
inflation was on the rise, investment was at an all-time low and
foreign policy was in tatters as the ruling coalition partners
remained embroiled in squabbles.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is taking place against the backdrop of repeated
offers of support to Congress by several non-BJP parties including
Rashtriya Loktantrik Morcha and the Communist Party of India
(Marxism) in taking the initiative to pull down the government led
by Atal Bihari Vajpayee and form an alternative one on the basis
of a common minimum program.
</P>
<P>
Sonia said the constituents of the coalition were engaged in an
internecine war bringing to the fore contradictions among them day
after day, as the allies of the BJP spoke in different voices on
various national and international issues.
</P>
<P>
In her 45-minute speech, the Congress president said her party
had never opposed for the sake of opposition but only highlighted
the "failures and follies" of the BJP-led government and would
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
In what is seen here as her most important address in recent
years, Sonia Gandhi set the tone for new political alignments by
stressing that Congress could take the lead in allying with the
left against the BJP block.
</P>
<P>
"We must take up the ideological crusade against the communal
forces from whatever source it arises," she told the Congress
leaders.
</P>
<P>
She said economic reforms in the country should be free from
dogma and be flexible so that they benefit all sections of the
society, adding that economic policy should be multi-dimensional
to meet the needs of the people at various levels.
</P>
<P>
The Congress president attacked the "confused and unclear"
foreign policy of the Vajpayee government towards China and
Pakistan, adding that it made no effort to mend ties with India's
traditional allies who opposed its nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
"Peace with our neighbors is an essential prerequisite. But in
a matter of a few weeks, the present coalition government
destroyed what the Congress had painstakingly achieved over a
ten-year period to normalize our relations with China," said Sonia
Gandhi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
