<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament to Discuss DRC, Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni will meet his parliamentary caucus Sunday over the
deepening crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and
the controversial suspension of privatization process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, usually monthly routine, was arranged after
Museveni called from Durban, South Africa where he was attending
the Non-Aligned Movement summit.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who returned from the summit Friday, is expected to
discuss the volatile situation in the DRC and Uganda's position
on the matter, a report of the New Nation said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Some parliamentarians told the newspaper that the suspension
by the Parliament of the privatization process will also be high
on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The recent fiasco of the Banyamulenge rebel campaign in the
southwest of the DRC and the diplomatic isolation of Uganda and
Rwanda who are alleged to be backing them, threaten to box
Kampala in a cold corner.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Museveni made it clear that Uganda opposes
allied intervention in the DRC conflict because it cannot address
the political issues and cannot solve the problem once and for
all.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Ugandan parliamentarians let out a loud cry
for suspension of the privatization process due to the rampant
corruption in it.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said some senior officials demanded huge sums of
kickback in the purchase of parastatals.
</P>
<P>
However, the state minister for finance in charge of
privatization Matthew Rukikaire is reported to have slapped the
legislature in the face when he declared that he would cooperate
with a probe of the process but would defy parliament and press
ahead with the privatization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
