<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks U.N. Help on Locating Missing Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran has urged the United
Nations to send a fact-finding team to Afghanistan to find out the
fate of the missing Iranian diplomats, the official news agency
IRNA reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi issued the demand at an
urgent meeting Friday with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Annan
in Durban of South Africa, where they were attending the
Non-aligned Movement summit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held amid reports that 11 Iranian diplomats,
reportedly captured by the Afghan Taliban militia in Mazari Sharif
in northern Afghanistan last month, may have been killed.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi told Annan that the reports of the killing were
extremely alarming, stressing that the Afghan Taliban militia
bears full responsibility for the safety of Iranian diplomats,
journalist and all other Iranian nationals.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Annan, Kharrazi said the U.N. chief
promised to work closely with Iran to make arrangements for the
immediate dispatch of the team.
</P>
<P>
Annan also assured Kharrazi that the U.N. would do everything
possible to prevent further crisis and defuse tension in
Afghanistan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that the Taliban kidnapped 11 Iranian diplomats,
an IRNA reporter and 35 truck drivers on August 8 when the
militia took over Mazari Sharif, the main stronghold of
Iran-backed anti-Taliban Northern Alliance led by the ousted
President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban repeatedly denied knowing the whereabouts
of the Iranian diplomats and the IRNA reporter and only admitted
the captivity of the truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
Some reports from Afghanistan said that the Iranian diplomats
and journalist were killed when the Taliban forces occupied
the Iranian consulate in Mazari Sharif on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses were quoted as saying that their bodies were left
in the consulate for two days before being buried in a mass grave
at the Sultan Razieh girls school.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian officials insisted that the group of Iranians
are still alive and kept by the Taliban in Qandahar, Taliban's
headquarters in southern Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
