<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Attracts More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The unique folklore culture,
Yellow River scenery, ruins of the mysterious Kingdom of Western
Xia regime (1038-1227) have made Ningxia, home to Chinese muslims,
a popular tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region of the Hui ethnic group played host to
half a million Chinese and overseas tourists in the first half of
this year, a year-on-year increase of 11.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite all its charm, the region was a late comer China's
tourism industry, and began to receive the first group of overseas
tourists in 1982. The regional tourism bureau was set up four
years later.
</P>
<P>
However, Ningxia's travel industry has made leaps and bounds in
recent years, and the region has opened a number of tourism zones
covering some scenic sites of great interest and is offering six
"golden routes" to both domestic and overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Ningxia received more than 4,200 tourists from
overseas and 1.57 million domestic visitors, as against 1,950
overseas arrivals and 500,000 domestic visits in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A French girl, now studying in Zhejiang University in east
China, said after a trip to Ningxia that she used to take Ningxia
for America's west but she unexpectedly came across water scenery
and vivid landscapes as beautiful as greeneries in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Tourism experts expected that with the continued improvement of
transportation facilities in China's western regions, more and
more tourists will flock to Ningxia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
