<HEADLINE> Iranian Vice President to Pay Landmark Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian First Vice President
Hassan Habibi is to pay a landmark visit to Iraq later this month
to sign "a significant agreement" with his Iraqi counterpart Taha
Yassin Ramadan, the Tehran Times reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The draft of the agreement has already been prepared by
experts of the two countries who met recently in Baghdad," the
daily quoted an informed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The source said the two countries have agreed on the
implementation of the U.N. Security Council Resolution 598 that
ended the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
The resolution covered issues of the exchange of prisoners of
war, sharing water on the Arvand Rud, exchanging visits of the
nationals in both countries, ensuring border security to prevent
smuggling and fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also agreed that the Iranian outlawed Mujaheddin Khalq
Organization (MKO) would be "thrown out" from the country, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, Tehran's main armed opposition group based in Iraq,
has launched a series of attacks on Iranian interests inside and
outside Iran. Last month, two MKO members assassinated former
head of the country's Prison Organization Assadollah Lajevardi in
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The group, declared illegal by Iranian authorities in 1981, is
still one of the main hurdles for Tehran and Baghdad to normalize
their relations 10 years after the end of the Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
The source also said that the two sides agreed to share
the water on Arvand Rud according to the Algiers Accord
signed in 1975 in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will provide official guarantees for the
safety and security of visitors of both sides and will also do all
to maintain peace on their borders to prevent any infiltration of
terrorists or smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
