<HEADLINE> Search Continues for Swiss Plane's Flight Data Recorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Investigators are continuing
their search for the two flight data recorders from Swissair
Flight 111 which could be crucial in explaining the plane's
devastating crash off Canada.
</P>
<P>
Two days after the tragic crash of Swissair Flight 111, there
has been no clear word about the cause or any sign of the black
box recorders.
</P>
<P>
Canadian investigators Friday listened to tapes of
conversations between the crew and air traffic controllers in
Moncton, New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
However, according to investigators, the pilots spoke calmly,
and though they said they had an emergency, they never sent out
the traditional call of "Mayday".
</P>
<P>
The investigators appeared to be leaning toward pilot error or
mechanical failure as causes of the crash, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
All 229 passengers and crew are believed to be dead. Efforts
have now been shifted from the rescue operation to search and
salvage.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a Canadian navy submarine was called in to help find
the recorders using sonar and listening devices.
</P>
<P>
The two recorders can emit locator signals for 30 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
