<HEADLINE> King Sihanouk Presides Over Siem Reap Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 5 (Xinhua) -- King Norodom
Sihanouk presided over discussions between the three main
political parties in Siem Reap on Saturday on ways to resolve
Cambodia's month-long political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Cambodian People's Party (CPP),
Funcinpec and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) as well as the National
Election Committee (NEC) and the Constitutional Council took part
in the three-day meeting which ends on September 7.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, Second Prime Minister and vice-president of the CPP,
and Chea Sim, chairman of the CPP and president of the National
Assembly, did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen cancelled plans to attend because Prince Ranariddh and
Sam Rainsy, presidents of the two opposition parties, were not
taking part.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, the King stated its three aims: to restore
order and peace in Phnom Penh; to make it possible to convene the
first National Assembly session and make it function normally; and
to form new government.
</P>
<P>
But the King had no confidence to the results of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I do not have much hope that the three-day meeting will have
the positive result that I wish," he wrote in a message Friday.
"The parties had deep conflicts with each other and have not yet
agreed to make any concessions or compromises."
</P>
<P>
The weekend talks are expected to focus on the complaints and
appeals process that the opposition says favored the CPP.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec was represented by party Secretary-General Tol Lah,
Uk Vithun and Pok Than. Ranariddh was in Bangkok. While the SRP
sent Ou Bunlong, a legal adviser and other two party members to
attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won a majority seats of the National Assembly in the
July 26 election, but failed to win two-thirds of the seats needed
to form a new government by itself.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and the SRP insisted that their demands for
ballot-recounts, revotes in some areas, ballot reconciliation and
the use of an earlier seat formula more favorable to them, be met
before they will discuss forming a coalition government with the
CPP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
