<HEADLINE> IMF Package Not Working, Say Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) package has not succeeded in pulling Thailand out of
its economic doldrums, a seminar concluded here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since Thailand's economy has not yet recovered despite spending
a year under the IMF reforms, the IMF package is a wrong solution,
said financiers and academics attending the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had made a mistake in exposing Thailand to
international market movements, National Finance Plc senior
executive Chartichai Palasuk said at the seminar entitled "Does
the IMF Have Good Intentions Towards Thailand?"
</P>
<P>
The IMF came to Thailand's rescue with a
17.2-billion-U.S.-dollar package after the baht depreciation
plunged the country into a financial crisis. But the IMF aid would
not materialize unless Thailand carried out IMF-proposed drastic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Chartichai, who had previously been employed by the IMF, said
the biggest IMF mistake was that it underestimated the problem of
capital flight. Because of massive capital flight, Thailand needs
26.1 billion dollars in capital inflow over the next 10 months or
so to overcome the present tight liquidity.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, he said, also made wrong predictions that foreign
lenders would cease calling back short-term loans to Thailand and
become more confident that the country would pay them back.
However, when the Bank of Thailand's swap obligation was
disclosed, the loans got called back to a greater extent than
before.
</P>
<P>
The IMF worked out its measures in negligence of the fact that
foreign investors were concerned that Thailand's financial
institutions remained unviable, thus putting Thailand in an
unfavorable position, Chartichai said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is still suffering from capital flight as foreign
creditors keep calling back loans, he added.
</P>
<P>
The solution set at the IMF's suggestion is to create a dollar
income through net export, long-term overseas borrowings and
selling of the country's assets. But some experts pointed out that
all these would be hard to come true as they depend on
international market conditions, which are very volatile.
</P>
<P>
The negative economic growth of Thailand for this year would
be seven to eight percent, worse than what the IMF previously
predicted, said the experts.
</P>
<P>
They noted that while the crisis was attacking the real sector
and labor market, the IMF still focused on solving the problems of
financial institutions, even though they represented only 10
percent of the country's fiscal woes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
