<HEADLINE> 13 Die, 100 Missing in Boat Capsize in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 13 people died and a
hundred others were missing in a ferry boat capsize in a river of
Bangladesh Friday afternoon, media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The mechanized ferry boat carrying over-capacity passengers
sank at about 5:00 p.m. in Shaniazan river, a tributary of the
turbulent Teesta river running through northwest part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
As rescue operation continued, villagers and also officials
feared many of those missing might have been drowned in the river.
</P>
<P>
There were at least 125 passengers in the boat that was
overturned by strong currents coming from upstream across the
border, and only the boatman and two others could avert the
tragedy by swimming ashore, a witness said.
</P>
<P>
Divers of the fire service from three local districts have been
called out for a massive rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
The death toll might be higher, as search for the rest of the
passengers continued, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Local administration, backed by villagers and the Bangladeshi
troops from the No.27 Battalion, continued rescue operation since
the boat capsized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
