<HEADLINE> Thai Liquidity Easing: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT) has
revealed that the liquidity crunch is easing owing to lower
withdrawals at financial institutions and lower short-term
interest rates in the repurchase market.
</P>
<P>
Since August last year to September this year, Thai commercial
bank deposits had risen by eight percent, "a satisfactory level
given the present economic conditions," BOT Governor Chatumongol
Sonakul said in remarks published Saturday by the Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The central bank Friday auctioned bonds worth 17.5 billion baht
(410 million U.S. dollars) at a lower yield compared to the level
last week.
</P>
<P>
The one-year government bonds had been auctioned at a yield of
11.9 percent, compared to previous bonds at 12.5 percent. The rate
has been steadily declining from 14.25 percent on June 22.
</P>
<P>
This is the 11th in a weekly series of issues totaling 500
billion baht (12.5 billion dollars) to replenish BOT's rescue fund
for financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Since the rates are aimed at setting benchmarks for banks the
declining level is likely to pull down lending rates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the 11th issue had been over-subscribed
by 2.72 times, with bids in the range of 11.5 to 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said that at present, government bonds held by
financial institutions account for 15 to 16 percent of the gross
national product (GNP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
