<HEADLINE> 12th Rio Group Summit Opens in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The 12th Rio Group annual
summit opened here Friday with 10 Latin American presidents
attending the event.
</P>
<P>
Regional peace and security and financial crises in Asia and
Russia are expected to be at the top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Rio Group delegates will also discuss efforts to fight
terrorism and the trafficking of drugs and illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
They will review measures to respond to the effects of world
financial crisis on the region and ways to maintain a steady
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Brazil, Argentina and Uruguay did not attend the
suumit.
</P>
<P>
With increased political and trade ties with the European
Union, the Rio Group leaders will talk about ways to strengthen
relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, host Panamanian President
Ernesto Perez Balladares called for more consultations on security
mechanisms among the member nations.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Panama would work to ensure the safe operation
of the Panama Canal after its return from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Eight nations -- Colombia, Mexico, Panama, Venezuela,
Argentina, Brazil, Peru and Uruguay -- founded the Rio Group in
Rio de Janeiro in 1986. Bolivia, Chile, Ecuador, and Paraguay
joined later.
</P>
<P>
El Salvador representing Central America and Guyana
representing the Caribbean are the temporary representatives for
their regions. 
</P>
