<HEADLINE> More State-Owned Cinemas to Be Privatized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Nine more state-owned cinemas
in various cities of Myanmar will be fully privatized for
continuous business operation as part of the country's
privatization scheme, according to the Privatization Commission
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The cinemas to be sold through competitive bidding include
those in Yangon, Bago, Myaungmya, Maubin, Mandalay, Pyin Oo Lwin
and Amarapura.
</P>
<P>
The cinemas also include those nationalized during the time of
the Revolutionary Council, the former government in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
From January to August, over 145 state-run cinemas in various
states and divisions have been designated to be privatized.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a 30-ton state-owned rice mill in Thanatpin, Bago
division, will also be sold to local entrepreneurs, according to
the Saturday's official paper the New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than two dozen state-owned saw mills in the
country have been reportedly privatized.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar announced privatization of 51 state-owned
economic enterprises (SEEs) in the first phase in January 1995,
the privatization process has been under way in various forms
including auctioning and leasing out the SEEs or establishing
joint ventures with local and foreign entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
