<HEADLINE> Most Thai Army Vehicles Made Idle Due to Fuel Budget Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The economic recession took
its toll in Thai army as about 25,000 or 80 percent of army
vehicles have been made idle with tyres and batteries removed
because the army's fuel budget has been cut by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cost-cutting measures ordered by the army chief, General
Chettha Thanajaro, have left only 20 percent of all army vehicles
in operation, the Bangkok Post newspaper said Saturday, quoting an
army source.
</P>
<P>
The army has 22 divisions, 62 regiments, 248 battalions and 744
companies.
</P>
<P>
Army officers, who used to get 200 liters of gasoline a month
for their position cars, now have to pay for fuel and repairs from
their own pockets, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Many of them have also turned to pooled vans to reduce the
expenses of using their own vehicles, he added.
</P>
<P>
Besides the fuel budget cut, General Chettha has also ordered
all army units to use water and electricity sparingly.
</P>
<P>
The units have to pay for themselves any water and power use
beyond permitted hours.
</P>
<P>
As a result, most of their air-conditioners have been left
unused, the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
