<HEADLINE> Colombian International Reserves Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's
international reserves dropped to 8.8 billion U.S. dollars at the
end of August from 10.3 billion dollars in August last year.
</P>
<P>
Leonardo Del Villar, executive board member of the Bank of the
Republic, said the central bank had to spend some of its reserves
to avoid the drastic devaluation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fall, the amount of hard currency was enough to
defend the new exchange band, modified on Wednesday to permit a
bigger devaluation of the peso, which could hit 23 percent this
year, Villar said.
</P>
<P>
The 8.8 billion dollars in reserves "gives us a big capability
to defend the new exchange band" in case the pressures against the
peso intensified, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Bank of the Republic had "other monetary
instruments" to prevent the peso from devaluing beyond what had
been foreseen in the band within which the Colombian currency
floats. 
</P>
