<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Insists on Antibiotics Ban, Despite EU Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Sweden will continue to ban
the use of antibiotics in animal food, a practice that is allowed
in the rest of the European Union (EU), despite the EU requirement
for it to act in accordance with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Antibiotics are used in farm animal food to induce growth,
while recent study indicates that bacteria in animals may develop
resistance to antibiotics, which in turn affects humans.
</P>
<P>
Sweden banned the use of antibiotics in 1986. When it joined
the EU in 1995, the country was given an exemption from the law
which allows the use of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
The exemption is due to expire on this December 31.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Minister of Agriculture Annika Ahnberg has demanded a
meeting with the EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler in an
effort to extend the exemption.
</P>
<P>
The minister was optimistic, but stressed that if the verdict
was not in Sweden's favor it will put up a fight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Economy to Register a 5 Percent Increase in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chilean economy is
growing this year at a real rate of five percent, announced
Chilean President Eduardo Frei on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to the Chamber of Commerce, Industry and
Agriculture of Panama during a two-day official visit before
taking part in the 12th Summit of the Rio Group.
</P>
<P>
Chile was in its fifth year with a single digit inflation, with
a rate that could be 4.5 percent this year, if the trend was
maintained, said Frei.
</P>
<P>
The economic stability had solid roots in 13 consecutive years
of budget surplus and a high level of national savings. The rate
of investment in fixed capital was 33 percent of the gross
domestic product in 1997, added Frei.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of foreign investment increased from 1.32
billion dollars in 1990 to 5.04 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We joined the Mercosur (the Southern Common Market) countries
in 1996, last year we signed the first free trade agreement with
Canada, and this year we expanded our agreement with Mexico," he
said. "We are ready to start a free trade agreement with the
European Union, within a general agreement we signed in 1996."
</P>
<P>
Frei ended his visit to Panama this afternoon and will take
part in the 12th the Rio Group Summit opening tonight at the
National Theater here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
