<HEADLINE> Mercosur Cities Call For Further Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The heads of cities in five
South American countries have agreed to cooperate in fighting
crime and improving standards of living for their residents.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three mayors, prefects and intendants of municipal
governments within the South America's largest trading bloc,
Mercosur, pledged to increase integration during the fourth
meeting of Mercocities, which will end Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration of Montevideo, issued by the city leaders, also
called for cooperation on improving the environment and fighting
corruption.
</P>
<P>
It highlighted political democracy and human rights in the
region, condemned all kinds of terrorism and emphasized the need
to improve standards of living.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the city of Montevideo signed a
cooperation agreement with Santiago, the capital of Chile.
</P>
<P>
Montevideo Intendant Mariano Arana was elected president of the
council and the executive secretariat of the Mercocities network.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Buenos Aires, Brasilia, Rio de Janeiro,
Santiago, Asuncion, and Montevideo, among others, were present at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, or the Southern Common Market, groups Argentina,
Brazil, Chile, Paraguay and Uruguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
