<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Plans For Expanding Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang will
continue to tap its tourism resources and increase its presence in
the Asian market despite the financial turmoil that has greatly
harmed local economy.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Provincial Tourism Bureau targeted Japan, Hong
Kong and Taiwan as three priorities for the second half of this
year and 1999 in its tourism promotion plan.
</P>
<P>
Regular promotions in South Korea and Southeast Asian countries
will remain as usual.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of Asian tourists dropped 16.3 percent in
the first half of this year, they still account for 64.6 percent
of the total number of overseas tourists visiting the province, as
statistics indicate.
</P>
<P>
The decrease of Asian tourists was also partially attributed to
the relatively poor services offered by travel agencies, backward
transportation and lack of adequate products aimed at tourism in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Besides improving these conditions, the Asian financial turmoil
has forced tourism agencies to step up their promotions in order
to face severe challenges from their overseas counterparts, said
the bureau official.
</P>
<P>
Xu Peng, a marketing official from the provincial tourism
bureau, said the province is to allocate special funds starting
next year to build up the image of Zhejiang's tourism industry
abroad.  
</P>
