<HEADLINE> More AIDS Patients Found in South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The number of AIDS patients
and virus carriers is on rise in south China's Guangdong Province,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A provincial health official, who declined to be named, said
that in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone alone, a total of 21
people have been detected as HIV carriers and one person has died
of AIDS, the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
The official did not disclose the total number of AIDS patients
and virus carriers in the province for the first half year. While,
in 1997, more than 80 people in the province were diagnosed as
having the AIDS virus, he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the HIV carriers, 37 are local residents, 30 come from other
Chinese provinces and regions and 13 are foreign people, the paper
quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are drug abusers, and some contracted the AIDS
virus during sexual activities, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
The official urged residents to shun casual sex and to be
faithful to their spouses to prevent spreading the fatal disease.
He also underlined the importance of raising public awareness.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province started testing for AIDS in the middle of
the 1980s. The first AIDS virus carrier was detected in 1986. He
was an African student in Guangdong, capital of the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
