<HEADLINE> Flood Donations Enthusiasm Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Floodwaters in China's major
swollen rivers have begun to subside, but people's enthusiasm in
helping the disaster victims is still on the rise, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Day by day, trucks,laden with disaster relief materials have
been shuttling from downtown Jingzhou to surrounding
flood-affected counties and districts.
</P>
<P>
Within the city, a new donation drive is being launched
encouraging municipal government officials and staffs to donate 50
to 100 percent of their August salaries.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is forcing them to do this--they are doing it on their
own accord," Zhang Xiuping, an official with Jingzhou local
government was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Liu Keyi, the city's Party secretary, initiated the donation
campaign after visiting the flood-ravaged regions.
</P>
<P>
Flooding had killed 133 people and destroyed 10 million
hectares of cultivated fields in areas around Jingzhou, Hubei
Province, by August 31.
</P>
<P>
The flood had also inundated 500,000 homes and led to the
relocation of 750,000 people, causing 14.88 billion yuan (1.79
billion US dollars) in losses to the city.
</P>
<P>
The first round of donations of money and materials by staffs
of the city government and enterprises directly under the
government have been valued at 3.8 million yuan (457,800 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"This time, besides money, cotton coats and quilts are
preferred as winter is approaching," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
