<HEADLINE> Nine Overseas Banks Apply for RMB Yuan Deal in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Nine of the foreign banks in
the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone (SEZ) have officially applied
for the right to run local currency business activities, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Their applications were submitted to the Shenzhen Branch of the
People's Bank of China (PBOC) in south China's Guangdong Province
for approval.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, PBOC, China's central bank, announced that
Shenzhen would be the second city in China to open its Renminbi
business to foreign banks after Shanghai, where nine overseas
banks were granted licenses at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The decision is viewed as a positive step in improving the
domestic banking sector. Also, foreign enterprises will benefit
from the news since by running Yuan business, foreign banks will
be able to offer more convenient services, said Zhou Bo, director
of the strategic development department of the Shenzhen branch of
the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
It would help curb underground market activities and improve
the investment environment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhou also anticipated a new round of competition among banks in
the long run which would prompt domestic banks to increase the
number and quality of their services, thus enlarging the banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, which hosted the first foreign bank in China, boasts
53 foreign financial institutions including 25 foreign bank
branches.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, total assets of foreign financial
institutions in the city amounted to 6.2 billion U.S. dollars,
accounting for 16.3 percent of the total in the country and their
profits represented 30.1 percent of the country's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
