<HEADLINE> Anti-flood Measures Mitigated Destruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China's anti-flood measures,
particularly those reinforced in recent years, have helped prevent
flood damage estimated at 710 billion yuan (85.5 billion US
dollars), today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
These measures include levees built along the flood-prone
rivers, large reservoirs situated near the rivers, large-scale
drainage of water-logged fields, and the hard work of professional
emergency squads, the daily quoted the Ministry of Water Resources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Current official statistics show that damage, particularly that
caused by the severe flooding along the Yangtze River and the
Songhua River in the northeast China so far amounts to some 167
billion yuan (20 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, water conservancy projects and other flood-control
efforts have prevented vast areas of land, incorporating more than
200 cities, from being inundated, water officials were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
This summer, levees along the middle stretches of the Yangtze
from the cities of Shishou to Hukou have ensured the safety of
more than 60 million people, 3.3 million hectares of farmland and
numerous key cities and industrial towns such Wuhan, Jiujiang and
Yueyang, as well as preventing major damage to the Beijing-Kowloon
and Beijing-Guangzhou railways.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that anti-flood measures along this stretch of
the Yangtze prevented 300 billion yuan (36.1 billion US dollars)
of damage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
