<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Forecasted in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains are expected to
fall on Indonesia from this month until early next year, the
Jakarta Post Saturday quoted the head of Meteorology and
Geophysics Agency Sri Diharto as saying.
</P>
<P>
The agency warned of possible floods and an adverse effect on
harvests as a result of above average precipitation which is
expected to last for between three and eight months depending on
the region.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the expected high rainfall could be the La Nina
weather phenomenon, Diharto said.
</P>
<P>
La Nina features colder-than-normal ocean temperatures in the
Pacific and sometimes follows the drought-inducing El Nino weather
pattern. El Nino is the opposite to La Nina and involves the
warming of the eastern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
La Nina is expected to bring heavy rains to Southeast Asia but
drought to parts of South America this year.
</P>
<P>
Diharto said he hoped the relevant government agencies would
begin to draft contingency plans for severe weather immediately.
</P>
<P>
He also warned of flash floods, recalling that Jakarta was hit
by floods attributed to La Nina in the first two months of 1996
that claimed the lives of 32 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
