<HEADLINE> World's First Monograph on Plague Found in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The "Special Collection on the
Plague", the world's first monograph created by a Chinese doctor
in the late 19th century, has been discovered in Ningbo, east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery will provide valuable clues for studies and
research related to traditional Chinese medical science, the
control of epidemic and medical literature," according to one
medical expert.
</P>
<P>
Doctor of Shicheng City Luo Zhiyuan in south China's Guangdong
Province in 1890 authored the work based on prescriptions of his
friend and a noted Chinese physician named Luo Zicun. as well as
on his own personal clinical experience in "treatment to relieve
internal heat or fever". The work's 17 parts cover wide-ranging
subjects, including the plague, pathogeny, symptoms, diseases,
abnormal pulse rates, medical records, viruses, pathology and case
studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
