<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MeEnroe Nominated For Induction to Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- John McEnroe of the United
States is among the five who have been nominated for induction
into the International Tennis Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
McEnroe, the youngest ATP world number one in 1980 at age 21,
won four U.S. Open and three Wimbledon titles.
</P>
<P>
Ken McGregor of Australia, Rex Bellamy and Derek Hardwick of
Britain and American Bob Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
McGregor was a member of the Australian Davis Cup championship
teams from 1950 to 1952 and teamed with Frank Sedgman to achieve
the only men's doubles Grand Slam sweep in 1951.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy was a London tennis writer from 1956 to 1983.
Hardwick ran the governing body of men's tennis before the ATP
Tour began. Kelleher is a former US Tennis Association
president. 
</P>
