<HEADLINE> Hotel Room Rates Rise 10 Percent in Greater Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The average cost of a
hotel room in Greater Los Angeles increased nearly 10 percent
during the first half of the year, according to statistics
released by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
The average room rate climbed to 108.41 US. dollars a night,
about 9.44 U.S. dollars more per room than compared with the first
six months of 1997, the Los Angeles Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau
(LACVB) said.
</P>
<P>
Although economic turmoil in Asia has slowed tourism from the Far
East, particularly from Japan and South Korea, the bureau said,
business and convention travel to the region remained high.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of 1998, the Los Angeles Convention
Center was booked about 70 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
The LACVB predicted that hotel room rates will continue to
climb as area hoteliers attempt to set their prices closer to
rates in other major cities, such as New York, which has an
average nightly room rate of 201.54 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The market here has been undervalued for a long time," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The occupancy rates, currently between 75 percent to 80 percent,
probably won't rise because the regional hotel market has hit its
"effective capacity" -- an industry standard that predicts how
many bookings a hotel can hope for in a given market, the report
pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
