<HEADLINE> Foreigners Jailed for Trafficking Heroin in Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Central Jakarta District
Court Friday sentenced three foreigners to between 6 and 14 years
in prison for trafficking and possessing a total of 6.6 kilograms
of heroin in different sessions, the Jakarta Post reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The three defendants were Colling Nyi Bongo from Malawi, and
Nigerians Emeka Simon Eloka and Christian Chukwu.
</P>
<P>
Colling, a former Malawian policeman, was sentenced to 14 years
in jail and was fined 5 million rupiah (500 U.S. dollars) for
trafficking 3.7 kilograms of heroin in November last year.
</P>
<P>
Colling provided information during his interrogation which led
police to arrest Emeka and Christian, who were staying in a rented
room in Central Jakarta. Police confiscated 2.9 kilograms of
heroin from the two Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced Emeka and Christian to 9 years and 6 years
in jail respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police have successfully cracked down on another
illegal drug ecstasy factory Friday, the second bust in a week.
</P>
<P>
Two men were arrested and materials used to make the drug
confiscated, according to the Indonesian Observer Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The raw materials confiscated are enough to produce 800,000
ecstasy pills worth up to 16 billion rupiah (1.6 million U.S.
dollars) if sold at the minimum price of 20,000 rupiah each,
Commander of the National Detective and Crime Directorate Maj.
Gen. Da's Bachtiar said.
</P>
<P>
On August 27, police publicized their first ever factory bust
and declared war on all manufacturers and distributors of drugs.
</P>
