<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark Has the Highest Taxes in the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Denmark has the highest
taxes in the world, showed the latest statistics released by the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The ranking is based upon 1996 tax revenues. Denmark topped in
1996 the high-tax-league with a tax of 52.2 percent, closely
followed by Sweden, with 52.0 percent. But preliminary figures
showed that in 1997 Swedish taxes amounted to 53,3 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
According to Unibank in Copenhagen, the Danish government
expects statistics to show that total taxes were lower, not
higher, in 1997. That means that Sweden may already have the
highest taxes.
</P>
<P>
Total taxes, defined as total tax revenues as a percentage of
GDP at market prices, increased in most OECD countries in 1996. On
average, taxes comprised 37.7 percent of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
