<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Production of Glass Utensils Growing in Shanxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The production of glass
utensils has developed rapidly in Qixian County in north China's
Shanxi Province in recent years.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest production center for glass utensils, Qixian
County has reached approximately 100 million yuan (12 million US
dollars) of annual output value. About 95 percent of the products
are exported to more than 50 countries and regions such as the
United States, Canada, France and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Qixian has a long history of glass utensil making, dating from
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) about 600 years ago. Glass utensils
produced here were used as tribute to emperors.
</P>
<P>
The county now has 35 enterprises involved in glass utensil
production with a work force of 8,500 and annual export earnings
of 95 million yuan (11.5 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Development of glass utensil production has also brought
profits to other sectors such as packaging and transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980905.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Turning Air Raid Shelters Into Shopping Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is exploiting its
web-like underground air raid shelters commercially, turning the
formerly dark and damp tunnels into noisy and busy business and
recreation centers.
</P>
<P>
Yang Sen, director of the city's civil defense office, said the
city has converted 1.5 million square meters of underground air
raid shelters into "underground streets," where locals and
tourists can find refuge from the summer heat, do business, and
have fun.
</P>
<P>
At the "underground city" at the People's Square in central
Shanghai, over 100 supermarkets, shops, bars, ballrooms,
barbershops and other businesses are operating. Tunnels further
below the city have become parking spaces capable of holding 600
cars.
</P>
<P>
Yang went on to say that Shanghai will continue to explore the
former defense tunnels to create additional living space for its
residents.
</P>
<P>
The city is building its first underground tunnel across the
Huangpu River, which crosses the city, and the tunnel will be
ready for use next year, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
