<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Possible Huge Quake Threatens New Zealand South Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- South Island of New Zealand
faces an earthquake of magnitude 8 on the Richter scale within the
 next few decades, a Wellington-based newspaper Saturday quoted an
influential panel of scientists as saying.
</P>
<P>
The warning comes only days after scientists predicted an
equally big earthquake in Wellington.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion reported that 20 scientists from New Zealand and
other countries emerged Friday from two days of talks in
Wellington to pool their research, including study on the dates of
rock falls and forest disturbances along the west coast of South
Island.
</P>
<P>
Kelvin Berryman of the Institute of Geological and Nuclear
Sciences of New Zealand was quoted as saying: "They do tend to
come in clusters. Whether this Alpine Fault earthquake is part of
the next cluster, we don't know."
</P>
<P>
"We're not talking next week. We're talking a longer time
frame, but with catastrophic results," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the scientists, the predicted massive earthquake
is overdue on the Alpine Fault, running from Hokitika to
Murchison.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the Alpine Fault has ruptured four
 times in the past 1,000 years, with each rupture producing an
earthquake of about magnitude 8. Approximate dates of the four
ruptures wee 1100, 1450, 1620 and 1717.
</P>
<P>
Berryman said that South Islanders could expect buildings to
sink, tilt or topple, and the earth to liquefy or slide away.
</P>
<P>
The scientists did not want to be "doomsayers". But it was
important to warn local and national authorities, "so they can
prepare to manage and mitigate the disaster", he said.
</P>
<P>
After the prediction of a strong Wellington earthquake was made
public Tuesday, the local TV station organized a discussion on
the topic of "Are you prepared when an earthquake hits" to raise
public awareness of the danger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
