<HEADLINE> Camdesus Says Latin American Economies on Right Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Latin American
economies are "on right track" and could finally resist the
current world-wide financial crisis, Michael Camdesus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following a two-day meeting of top
financial officials from 11 Western Hemisphere countries, Camdesus
said that he was "encouraged" by the atmosphere of the meeting,
which was convened amid financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"I was personally very impressed by the sense of realism but at
the same time the sense of purpose and the sense of togetherness
these ministers and governors were demonstrating in this
occasion," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"These are difficult times and times when, well, the temptation
is strong to get it alone," he said, adding that nobody tries to
"to escape from the constraints or to go to any kind of ostrich
policy."
</P>
<P>
Echoing sentiments expressed by several of the ministers,
Camdesus said financial markets "do not differentiate properly
among good (economic) players and those who are less convincing."
</P>
<P>
"The medium and long term outlook for Latin America in our
judgment remains strong," said Camdesus.
</P>
<P>
Camdesus said the IMF and its sister financial institutions
were prepared to strengthen and broaden their support for Latin
American countries and would consult closely in advance of their
annual meetings early next month on the best ways to do this.
</P>
<P>
Camdesus also said that even though the IMF's coffers have
been depleted by billion dollar rescue packages for Asia and
Russia the organization still had sufficient funds to carry out
its programs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the U.S. Senate's approval of 18 billion U.S.
dollars in new funding for the IMF, he said he was hopeful the
House will follow the Senate because by doing this the U.S. would
strengthen itself against market uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by the turmoil in Russia and Asia, stock markets
across Latin America and the U.S. are going down while the
currencies of some Latin American countries started to devalue.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts feared that the turmoil will result in a
crisis in the U.S. and then a recession around the globe.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the two-day meeting at the IMF headquarters was
to discuss the global financial turmoil and current prospects,
their impact on the Western Hemisphere, and the strategies of the
countries in the region to adapt to the more difficult external
environment.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody was coming here to ask for money... not because they
could believe that we wouldn't have enough to face the problem but
because they do believe that they have already done the right
things, that they are on the right track," Camdesus said.
</P>
<P>
In a communique after the first day of their meeting, the
officials said they will pursue "continued macroeconomic
stability" and implement "sound fiscal policies" in order to gain
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The will also maintain their current exchange rate policies and
regimes, open capital markets while continue and deepen their
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted that "the external environment had
deteriorated further in recent weeks, especially reflecting market
reactions to the crisis in Russia."
</P>
<P>
The officials agreed on the importance of strategies to better
manage risks associated with the volatility of international
capital flows.
</P>
<P>
"They called upon the international financial institutions to
continue to look at possible ways to respond to such volatility
and to report back on possible strategic and mechanisms," said the
communique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
