<HEADLINE> 12 Killed in Two US Military Helicopters Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Two United States Air Force
helicopters crashed early Friday during a training exercise in
Nevada, killing all 12 people on board, the service said.
</P>
<P>
The two HH-60G Pave Hawk helicopters from Nellis Air Force Base
crashed about 1 a.m. PDT (0800 GMT). The wreckage was found about
an hour later.
</P>
<P>
Base officials said that it was most likely the helicopters
collided before they crashed. But there was also possible the
helicopters both crashed into the rugged mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
The crash site is 40 kilometers north of Indian Springs, a
remote auxiliary airfield on the base about 72 kilometers
northwest of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
Built by Sikorsky Aircraft, the HH-60G helicopters normally
carry a crew of four people, two pilots, a flight engineer and a
gunner. But some, including the two that crashed, also carry two
rescue crew members.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has 99 HH-60G helicopters in use at 12 bases in
the United States and abroad. The Nellis helicopters were part of
the 66th Rescue Squadron, the Air Force's largest rescue squadron.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has 21 major aviation accidents, causing at least
one death or 1 million U.S. dollars damage, so far this fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
In the same period last year, the Air Force had 25 major
accidents and by the end of last fiscal year, the service
experienced 29 major crashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
