<HEADLINE> Roundup: Killing of Aliens Sparks Jitters in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Shang Xuqian)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The killing of three
foreigners, two from Senegal and one from Mozambique, on a train
near Pretoria Thursday has caused anxiety in South Africa as
growing xenophobia is feared.
</P>
<P>
Political parties and social groups Friday denounced the
incident in which the aliens were killed after a mob accused them
of stealing jobs from South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Two of the victims were electrocuted by overhead wires when
they tried to escape by climbing on the roof of the train. The
third was thrown out of a window and was run over by an oncoming
train.
</P>
<P>
The killing signaled rising xenophobia and detracted from the
real issues behind unemployment, human rights organizations,
academics and religious leaders said in a joint statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
The incident "bears testimony to the increasingly dangerous
manifestations of xenophobia in the country," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said a recent Human Rights Watch report had
documented how rising xenophobia in South Africa was further
marginalizing and endangering the already vulnerable group of
non-citizens legally staying in the country, including refugees.
</P>
<P>
A Cape Town group working with refugees had found a sharp
increase in violent attacks against refugees.
</P>
<P>
The group had reported the deaths of 33 foreigners so far this
year in attacks motivated solely by anti-foreigner sentiments.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress (ANC) condemned the
incident.
</P>
<P>
"The ANC condemns in the strongest possible terms the
abominable killing of our fellow Africans by people who do not
attach any value to human life," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This cruel killing of foreigners will create a wrong
perception that the South African people do not welcome
foreigners in this country, and may also undermine the efforts of
our government on the African renaissance."
</P>
<P>
"Our country does not have discriminatory policies against
foreigners. In fact, many foreigners are already contributing to
the reconstruction and development of our country, and we should
encourage them to continue to do so."
</P>
<P>
The South African Communist Party (SACP) said in a statement
that it was diversionary and xenophobic to blame unemployment on
the influx of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"To unleash popular frustrations against the poor of other
countries is a dangerous and diversionary ploy," it said.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment was the most serious crisis affecting society,
the SACP said, but is was not caused by the influx of poor
working people from neighboring countries or elsewhere in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The present turmoil in the Great Lakes region of Africa
should remind us of how dangerous xenophobic mobilization can
be," it warned.
</P>
<P>
Solutions to unemployment would instead come from focusing on
sustainable and coherent industrial policies, the SACP said.
</P>
<P>
Two political experts warned Friday that resentment toward
foreigners among South Africans could spark a pattern of violent
attacks against illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
Wrath toward illegal aliens was growing, and was especially
strong among black South Africans, South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted a political scientist, Theo Bekker, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"This is going to develop into a bloody battle if something is
not done," said Bekker of Pretoria University.
</P>
<P>
Steven Friedman, director of Center for Policy Studies, said:
"The scary part is the danger that a pattern will start
developing."
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that Thursday's incident was not the first of
its kind. More such assaults could be expected if intolerance
toward foreigners was not addressed.
</P>
<P>
Friedman said recent studies revealed a strong resentment
toward aliens, especially in Gauteng and Western Cape provinces.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing that it was impossible to stop the flow of illegal
aliens, Friedman and Bekker said that the government and
politicians should try to instill greater tolerance toward
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Friedman said there was nothing rational about hating all
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The perception that they robbed South Africans of jobs was not
necessarily true, he said, adding that many foreigners were
self-employed, and others were prepared to work for wages
unacceptable to South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Bekker said South Africa simply does not have the resources to
stop all unwelcome immigrants entering the country.
</P>
<P>
"It will eventually cost more to keep them away than providing
them with a livelihood," he said.
</P>
<P>
The solution is the economic development in neighboring
countries to produce job opportunities for those seeking a haven
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Until such time, the message from the government should be
that foreigners should be treated with leniency. If that doesn't
happen I see serious trouble coming," Bekker said.
</P>
<P>
A body calling itself the Unemployed Masses of South Africa
(UMSA) Friday denied that its members were responsible for the
deaths of the three aliens.
</P>
<P>
Police said UMSA members, who earlier on Thursday took part in
a protest march in Pretoria, were on the train.
</P>
<P>
So far, no arrests have been made owing to the fact that no
witnesses had come forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
