<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressional Leaders to Meet on Plan on Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Speaker Newt Gingrich,
Democratic leader Dick Gephardt and other top leaders of the U.S.
House of Representatives will meet next week to review plans for
receiving an expected report on President Bill Clinton from
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich agreed to the meeting in a phone conversation with
Gephardt, The Associated Press quoted unidentified officials as
saying.
</P>
<P>
There is no indication yet Starr has notified Congress that one
is ready for delivery, the AP said.
</P>
<P>
Gephardt's spokesman, Eric Smith, quoted the Missouri Democrat
as saying, "If this process must begin, it is among the most
serious responsibilities Congress will undertake and it must be
conducted in a truly bipartisan manner."
</P>
<P>
A Republican leadership aide, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that in the phone conversation, Gingrich "made
clear that he hoped the process would remain bipartisan. He hoped
the members would not prejudge until they have reviewed all the
evidence and that he had tremendous confidence in the ability of
Henry Hyde to lead this process," The AP reported.
</P>
<P>
Hyde is the Illinois Republican who chairs the Judiciary
Committee, which would have jurisdiction over any report Starr
submits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Senator Joseph Lieberman, a Democrat, said Clinton
deserves a formal "public rebuke" over his relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and a second lawmaker
suggesting presidential "public restitution" to make amends.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to ignore the impact of the misconduct the
president has admitted to on our children, our culture and our
national character," Lieberman said Thursday in a speech on the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
"Such behavior is not just inappropriate, it is immoral,"
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is on a visit in Dublin, Ireland, was quoted by
news reports as saying on Friday, "I can't disagree with anyone
else who wants to be critical of what I've already acknowledged is
inappropriate."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "There's nothing that he (Lieberman) or anyone
else could say in a personally critical way that I don't imagine I
would disagree with since I have already said it myself, to
myself, and I'm very sorry about it but there's nothing else I can
say."
</P>
<P>
Representative Marcy Kaptur, a Democrat, raised the subject of
Clinton's relation with Lewinsky in a speech before the Veterans
of Foreign Wars in San Antonio and later in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
"The more important word to me is restitution," she was quoted
by AP as saying. "The emphasis should be on the young people, and
how he as a father of a daughter and father of the nation can
exact some good of the situation."
</P>
<P>
Simply resigning would not do it, she added. "We need something
else -- he doesn't have to resign, or he could resign and then do
it."
</P>
<P>
The party's leaders, Gephardt in the House and Senator Tom
Daschle, have criticized the president's behavior but said they
want to see what Starr reports before rendering further judgment.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman said Thursday, the president had "compromised his
moral authority," damaged his credibility and complicated the
efforts of parents seeking to instill "values of honesty" in their
own children.
</P>
<P>
Some sort of "public rebuke" is called for, he said, possibly
through a resolution or censure or reprimand by Congress.
</P>
<P>
But any such action is premature before a Starr report is
issued and before the White House has a chance to respond to it,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
